@node "Overview" "Overview"
@tab 25
@{JRIGHT} Next section: @{"Requirements" LINK "Requirements"}@{line}
@{JCENTER}@{B}Aglet Modula-2 PPC Overview@{UB}
@{_LMARG_}@{line}@{JLEFT}
_______________________________________________________________@{line}

@{b}Introduction@{tab}@{" > " LINK "Introduction"}@{line}
Features@{tab}@{" > " LINK "Features"}@{line}
Limits@{tab}@{" > " LINK "Limits"}@{line}
Known Bugs@{tab}@{" > " LINK "Bugs"}@{line}
Future@{tab}@{" > " LINK "Future"}@{ub}@{line}
_______________________________________________________________@{line}

This is a Beta release of a native PPC Modula-2 compiler for Amiga OS4. @{_AGM2_} v3.1 Beta (5.4.2011) implements much of the ISO Modula-2 base standard.
@{_SMLDENT_}@{line}

@{B}@{FG Highlight}I make no representations about the suitability of this software
for any purpose. It is provided "as is" without express or implied warranty.@{FG Text}@{ub}@{line}
@{_LMARG_}

This is copyrighted freeware being distributed "as-is".  I hope it can be useful
for anyone interested in developing new generation Amiga software with a Wirthian language.@{line}
_______________________________________________________________@{line}

Even though this is a beta release, I believe the package is in a usable condition. I have successfully built a number of non-trivial programs with it:@{line}

@{tab}> @{i}ModLnk @{ui}, the pre-Linker used for building programs@{line}
@{tab}> The included @{i}M2IDE @{ui} development environment@{line}
@{tab}> @{i}IDLTm2 @{ui}, an IDLTool analogue for producing Interface DEFINITION modules@{line}
@{tab}> A test generator program, @{i}tgM2 @{ui}, for Modula-2@{line}
@{tab}> The @{i}GuideMaker @{ui} program on OS4Depot@{line} 
@{tab}> The @{i}LoggerWindow @{ui} program on OS4Depot@{line}
@{tab}> The compiler now compiles itself.@{line}
@{tab}> The @{i}Capture @{ui} Programmer's Challenge Game.@{line}

It goes without saying the compiler is not competitive with GCC for PPC code optimization, but it does a good job of creating correct machine code for a correct Modula-2 program.@{line}

Modula-2 is certainly a relatively "obscure" (at least in the U.S)
language, but far from a dead one. A number of compilers are available without cost for different platforms. There is an ISO standard and most newer compilers, including @{_AGM2_}, cleave closely enough to the standard to achieve good portability.@{line}

M2 does offer some things you don't get with C:@{_SMLDENT_}@{line}

A better approach to building modular software - You don't have to spend 50% of your development time figuring out why your "make" file does not work.     :)@{line}

A cleaner, simpler language than C, offering a better type system, more rational array handling, much better design for modular programming supporting Abstract Data Types and much greater opportunity to change module implementations without propagating complexity and uncertainty.@{line}

Included Amiga-oriented support modules designed to get you effectively using Intuition, Reaction, etc, without having to become an expert in all the details - Direct calls to almost all Amiga Libraries are available, but intermediate modules from Aglet like "SimpleGUI", "SimpleRequesters", "SimpleImageHander", "SimpleRexx", and "AmigaTimer" expose a straightforward interface to common needs.@{line}
@endnode
@node "Introduction" "Overview"
@{JRIGHT} Section head: @{"Overview" LINK "Overview"}@{line}
 Next subsection: @{"Features" LINK "Features"}@{line}
@{JCENTER}
@{B}Aglet Modula-2 PPC Introduction@{UB}

_________________________________________________________________________

@{JLEFT}@{_LMARG_}


@{_AGM2_} is a complete rewrite of my previous M68K compiler. The compiler has been redesigned as a front-end/back-end compiler with intermediate code production in order to open the potential for increased optimization and portability. Code is generated compatible to the SYSV ABI for PPC.@{line}

It implements much of the @{i}ISO 10514 Modula-2 Base Standard @{ui}, and (most of) the specified ISO standard libraries have been provided.  The AOS4 SDK is represented by modules containing Amiga System Library definitions and interfaces.@{line}

PPC native code is written out as an assembler language file, which is processed by @{i}as @{ui}, the GNU assembler delivered with the AOS4 SDK. A M2 pre-linker pulls together all the modules used by your program and implements inter-module version checking, then invokes @{i}ld @{ui} to create the executable.@{line}

The compiler has bootstrapped itself, so most modules compile very quickly. It does not yet do much in the way of optimization, but I think it offers simpler way to get into producing sophisticated native Amiga OS4 programs than @{i}gcc @{ui}.@{line}

It has roots in the @{i}Benchmark Modula-2 @{ui} compiler (which in turn has its roots in the ETH
one-pass compiler for the M68000). Many thanks to Jim Olinger of Armadillo Computing, with whom I worked for a number of years on the AmigaOS library support for @{i}Benchmark Modula-2 @{ui}. Though Jim is no longer active in Amiga matters, he expresses his support for this new M2 project building on what he provided the Amiga community in @{i}Benchmark Modula-2 @{ui}.
@endnode
@node "Features" "Aglet M2 Features"
@{JRIGHT} Section head: @{"Overview" LINK "Overview"}@{line}
 Next subsection: @{"Limits" LINK "Limits"}@{line}
@{JCENTER}
@{B}Aglet Modula-2 Features@{UB}

_________________________________________________________________________

@{JLEFT}@{_LMARG_}

The most important goal for @{_AGM2_} has been to provide a modern Amiga M2 compiler consistent with the ISO Modula-2 Standard. There is still a good deal to be done before it can be called ISO conformant, but much has been implemented.@{line}

For an overview of the Modula-2 language, see the section @{" Modula-2 " LINK "M2_Language"}.  
Notable language ISO additions which were not in Niklaus Wirth's @{i}Programming in Modula-2 @{ui} document include:@{_SMLDENT_}@{line}
> module termination (@{_M2_ "FINALLY"} section)@{line}
> an exception handling facility (@{_M2_ "EXCEPT"} section)@{line}
> the ISO standard library modules.
@{_LMARG_}@{line}

The compiler and pre-linker can be used from the CLI, but @{_AGM2_} also comes with a basic IDE: @{i}M2IDE @{ui} organizes compile order dependencies for you, presents a GUI for one button compiling and linking, integrates with a text editor, and has more features useful for larger projects.@{line}

@{_AGM2_} comes with Definition modules for direct calling of Amiga Libraries in AOS4, with parameters just as described in the SDK's AutoDocs (though in many case with improved item typing).@{line}

The ISO standard library provides platform independent modules supporting IO, Strings and number/string conversions, Math, multiprocessing/threading, and reading the system clock.@{line}

I've also included, as part of @{_AGM2_}, a fairly extensive set of Aglet support modules, both Amiga specific and of more generic interest. eg,@{_SMLDENT_}@{line}

- A number of Amiga-specific modules supporting a higher level useage of things like the Timer Device, Font access, ARexx, Amiga CLI argument processing, separate Amiga process startup, etc.@{line}

- A mixed bag of generally useful programming support modules for things such as@{_LRGDENT_}@{line}
> Dynamic Strings@{line}
> Binary Trees, Hash Tables@{line}
> QuickSort, Binary Search@{line}
> Regular Expressions@{line}
> Matrix Operations, Simultaneous Equations@{line}
> Huge Integers
@{_SMLDENT_}@{line}

- A module package, "SimpleGui", intended to simplify the use of Reaction without sacrificing capabilities.@{line}

- A module package, "SimpleGraphics", providing 2D drawing and graphing calls into Intuition windows and regions within windows.
@{_SMLDENT_}@{line}
@{_LMARG_}@{line}

-
@endnode
@node "Limits" "Limits"
@tab 70
@{JRIGHT} Section head: @{"Overview" LINK "Overview"}@{line}
 Next subsection: @{"Known Problems" LINK "Bugs"}@{line}
@{JCENTER}@{B}Limitations@{UB}

_________________________________________________________________________@{line}
See also: @{" Known Problems " LINK "Bugs"} @{" LowLevel " LINK "LowLevel"}  @{" ISO " LINK "ISO"}@{line}
@{JLEFT}@{_LMARG_}

@{_HEADING_ "Compiler"}

In general, limits are imposed only by the amount of memory available and the 32 bit size of the computer word used by the compiler. Some other details:@{line}

size of procedure/Module@{tab}-> Current limiting factor is how many live vars a proc creates (1024).@{line}

length of string literals@{tab}-> One line of text@{line}
number of dimensions of open arrays@{tab}-> 1@{line}
number of enumeration literals@{tab}-> 256@{line}
number of coroutines@{tab}-> 0  (Coroutines NYI)@{line}

ISO features not yet implemented:@{_LRGDENT_}@{line}
64 bit INTEGER/CARDINAL@{line}
tagged NEW/DISPOSE@{line}
structured type constructors@{line}
literal string append operations@{line}
multidimensional open arrays@{line}
dynamic modules@{line}
type COMPLEX
@{_LMARG_}@{line}

@{_HEADING_ "Linker"}

No facilities yet to support Amiga Library creation.@{line}
Linking of modules into object file archives not yet implemented.@{line}
"*.so" library usage not yet addressed.@{line}
@{_LMARG_}

@{_HEADING_ "IDE"}

AOS File Notification not yet used for source change status.@{line}
@endnode
@node "Bugs" "Bugs"
@{JRIGHT} Section head: @{"Overview" LINK "Overview"}@{line}
 Next subsection: @{"Future" LINK "Future"}@{line}
@{JCENTER}
@{B}Known Problems@{UB}

_________________________________________________________________________

@{JLEFT}@{_LMARG_}

@{_HEADING_ "Open arrays of SYSTEM types"}
Parameters which are open arrays of SYSTEM types (e.g., ARRAY OF WORD, ARRAY OF LOC) are not yet correctly implemented, eg. HIGH() may not be correct on these.
@{_LMARG_}@{line}

@{_HEADING_ "Grim Reaper during compile"}
Illegal memory accesses with incorrect source code may still occur. In most cases these are benign and you can continue with the compile after the GR by simply choosing "Continue Program". If not, see the notes in @{" VerboseCompile " LINK "VerboseCompile"}.
@{_LMARG_}@{line}

@{_HEADING_ "Wrong source position reported for some errors"}
The error position reported for parameter syntax errors always points to the closing parenthesis, rather than to the parameter that caused the error.
@{_LMARG_}@{line}

@{_HEADING_ "Local Module FINALLY bug"}
The compiler currently will not accept a local module does not have a FINALLY section. Use an empty section as a workaround.
@{_LMARG_}@{line}

@{_HEADING_ "Most Aglet support modules are not thread-safe"}
The Storage module is an exception, so threads (eg started from the ISO Processes module) can allocate and deallocate memory safely.
@{_LMARG_}@{line}
@endnode
@node "Future" "Future"
@{JRIGHT} Section head: @{"Overview" LINK "Overview"}@{line}
@{JCENTER}
@{B}Plans@{UB}

_________________________________________________________________________

@{JLEFT}@{_LMARG_}

@{_HEADING_ "Fix Known Bugs and Awkwardnesses"}
@{" Known Problems " LINK "Bugs"}
@{_LMARG_}@{line}

@{_HEADING_ "Compiler Robustness"}
The compiler does a good job of parsing correct M2 source code, but unfortunately there are currently still some circumstances in which a syntax error will evoke a Grim Reaper. Most of these are innocuous NIL dereferences so that the compiler can be continued from the GR, but all need to be fixed.
@{_LMARG_}@{line}

@{_HEADING_ "Code Generation"}
The compiler currently does only a little work attempting to improve the baseline correct (hopefully) intermediate and machine code. There is lots of work to be done improving this.
@{_LMARG_}@{line}

@{_HEADING_ "Modules as Amiga Libraries"}
To be done.
@{_LMARG_}@{line}

@{_HEADING_ "Modules as Static Libraries"}
This could decrease executable size from 0% to 20%, depending on the modules used.
@{_LMARG_}@{line}

@{_HEADING_ "ISO compatibility"}
Structured Constants@{line}
SYSTEM type parameters ISO-compliant@{line}
Dynamic Modules@{line}
Tagged Allocate/Deallocate@{line}
ISO-compliant CAST@{line}
Multi-Dimensional Open Arrays@{_LMARG_}@{line}

@{_HEADING_ "Overflow and Range Checking"}
Currently, the compiler does implement run-time overflow and range checking, but not consistently, ie, there remain many places where such checking could occur but, at this time, does not get inserted.
@{_LMARG_}@{line}

@{_HEADING_ "Object Oriented ISO Extensions"}
The ISO group also specified a standard for adding classes with inheritance to the base standard. I am quite interested in implementing this.
@{_LMARG_}@{line}



-
@endnode
@node "Requirements" "Requirements"
@tab 8
@{JRIGHT} Prev section: @{"Overview" LINK "Overview"}@{line}
 Next section: @{"Installation" LINK "Installation"}@{line}
@{JCENTER}
@{B}Aglet M2 Requirements@{UB}

_________________________________________________________________________@{line}
@{JLEFT}@{_LMARG_}

@{_HEADING_ "For Compiler and Linker "}

@{_ITM11_}> Amiga OS4.x up-to-date Installation. Development work is being done on AOS 4.1 update2.@{_ITEMEND_}

@{_ITM11_}> Hyperion SDK Installed@{_ITEMEND_}
@{_ITM19_}- SDK should be v53.8 or later.  Development work is being done on SDK 53.20.@{_ITEMEND_}
@{_ITM19_}- "as" and "ld" are called by the M2 compiler and linker, and must be accessible by the path "SDK:gcc/bin/" (as they will be after the usual SDK install).@{_ITEMEND_}
@{_ITM19_}- Transcendental and sqrt functions are implemented via the C library SDK:clib2/lib/libm.a@{_ITEMEND_}

@{_ITM11_}  The SDK is freely available at the Hyperion web site, http://www.hyperion-entertainment.biz/,
in the "Downloads" section.@{_ITEMEND_}

@{_ITM11_}> A directory for the Aglet M2 package (~20MB)@{_ITEMEND_}
@{_ITM19_}- e.g. "Work:AgletV3". I suggest that an Assign for this directory be created as "AGV3:".@{_ITEMEND_}

@{_ITM11_}> multi ASSIGN of "M2Lv3:" for supplied library modules@{_ITEMEND_}

@{_ITM11_}> "T:" assigned to a nice location for temporary files.@{_ITEMEND_}

The install will create an assign script you can insert or call from s:user-startup:@{_LRGDENT_}@{line}
@{b};---------------------------------------------------------------@{line}
; M2-Assigns.s     Assigns for Aglet Modula-2@{line}
;@{line}
assign agv3:  ; @{ub}@{i}<directory in which you installed Aglet M2 PPC>@{ui}@{b}@{line}
;@{line}
assign m2lv3: agv3:system agv3:amiga agv3:iso agv3:reaction agv3:sysmod agv3:experimental@{line}
;@{line}
path agv3: ADD@{line}
LOADWB NEWPATH   ; @{ub}@{i}<remove this line if the script is run in user-startup>@{ui}@{b}@{line}
;---------------------------------------------------------------@{ub}
@{_LMARG_}@{line}

@{_HEADING_ "For IDE "}

@{_ITM11_}> Arexx up and running@{_ITEMEND_}

@{_ITM11_}> An Arexx capable Editor@{line}
A "plugin" is currently provided for these editors@{_ITEMEND_}@{lindent 20}

@{i}GoldEd @{ui} (tested on v7.23)@{line}
@{i}TurboText @{ui} (tested on v2.0)@{line}
@{i}CygnusEd @{ui} (tested on v4.20)@{line}
@{i}MicroGoldEd @{ui} (probably works, is untested)@{line}
@{i}Annotate @{ui} (tested on v2.7.5 and v2.7.7)@{_ITEMEND_}

@{_ITM11_}   Others may be made available by implementing the ARexx commands in M2IDEEdtCmds.def following the patterns of the sources of the above plugins.@{_SMLDENT_}@{line}


.
@endnode
@node "Installation" "Installation"
@{JRIGHT} Prev section: @{"Requirements" LINK "Requirements"}@{line}
 Next section: @{"Modula-2 Language" LINK "M2_Language"}@{line}
@{JCENTER}-------------------------------------------------------------------------@{line}
@{B}Aglet M2 Installation@{UB}@{line}
-------------------------------------------------------------------------@{line}
@{JLEFT}@{_LMARG_}

@{_HEADING_ "To Install:"}

Unpack the AgletM2PPC.lha file into a temporary directory. This unpacks to three files, AgletM2PPCBin.lha, AgletM2PPCModSrc.lha, and an AmigaDOS script, DoInstallAgletM2PPC.s.@{line}

EXECUTE the script and it will allow you to choose a parent directory in which it will create a directory named "AgletV3" and distribute the LHA contents into a directory structure underneath.@{line}

It will also create a file, "m2-Assigns.s", which will do the required ASSIGN, "M2Lv3:" (see @{" Requirements " LINK "Requirements"}). This assign is used by the compiler to find the standard support modules' symbol and object files. You may want to add a call to this script from S:user-startup.@{line}

Other things you will have to do are:@{_LRGDENT_}@{line}

> Put the directory where the compiler executables were placed into your shell path.@{line}
e.g., Use the PATH ADD shell command. This directory was called "AGV3:" in @{" Requirements " LINK "Requirements"} so it would be, "PATH AGV3: ADD". You may want to add this command into S:shell-startup.@{line}

> If you don't have GoldEd as your editor, rename one of the other supported editor "front" programs to "EdtFront".@{line}
As of v0.3 (27.2.2010) you can instead explicitly give the name of your editor interface program. Use the
CLI -EDITOR switch, eg. "-Editor PROGDIR:cedfront"@{line}

> If you do have a the GoldEd (and the Cubic package), do visit OS4 Depot and download Frank Ruthe's materials for a very nice extended integration of M2 into GoldEd 8. Filed as "development/ide/agletm2cubic.lha" It includes a very detailed description of how to setup the various features of GoldEd for this purpose.@{line}
URL: http://os4depot.net/share/development/ide/agletm2cubic_lha.readme@{line} 

> Frank Ruthe has also designed some very nice icons for AgletM2 and given permission for me to include these with this distribution. You may want to set these as your system default icons for M2 source files and M2IDE project files.@{_SMLDENT_}@{line}

@{_LMARG_}
--------------------------------------------------
Notes
--------------------------------------------------@{line}

The executables are @{b}Mod2, Mod2Lnk, M2Err, IDLTm2@{ub} for the Compiler/Linker, and @{b}M2IDE, WindowLogger, EdtFront @{ub} for the IDE.@{line}

The IDE communicates with your selected editor via an intermediate program, named "EdtFront" (unless the -EDITOR switch was used). One of the supplied executables (GedFront, AnnFront, CedFront, or TtxFront) should be copied as file "EdtFront". Sources for these programs are supplied in case you want to write one for a different editor.


The "Name List" files, "#?.nl", are used by @{i}M2IDE @{ui} to exclude the standard support modules from the @{i}M2IDE @{ui} modules window, leaving only the modules you are working on for a specific project.


A GoldEd syntax file for Modula-2 syntax coloring is also provided. It goes into GoldEd/add-ons/Modula2/Syntax/Dictionaries. A similar syntax file suitable for Annotate is provided.


A few test and example program sources are unpacked into the "/Examples/" subdirectory.@{line}
@endnode
