@node "Modula-2" "Modula-2"
@{JRIGHT} Section head: @{"M2 Language" LINK "M2_Language"}@{line}
@{JCENTER}
@{B}Modula-2 Description@{UB}

_________________________________________________________________________

@{JLEFT}@{_LMARG_}

Modula-2 was designed and released in the '80s by Niklaus Wirth as the "serious" language for large application and system software to follow up on the "teaching" language, Pascal, that he had worked on in the '60s and '70s.


The major design idea was to foster reduction in complexity via "information hiding" while at the same time providing the programmer with all necessary tools for low level programming within the framework of a strongly typed language.


The public interface of a software module (which is the @{_M2_ "DEFINITION MODULE"}) is published separately from the code itself (which is the @{_M2_ "IMPLEMENTATION MODULE"}). 
If changes, or even major revisions of the code, are limited to the Implementation module, they need not propagate to other code that uses your module. Client code can see only what is in the Definition module.


Modula-2 thus provides an ideal platform for "Abstract Data Types": an ADT is a programmer-defined object type along with a collection of functions providing the complete set of allowable operations on the objects of that type.
The ADT approach fosters programming with objects, though some important features of true Object Oriented Programming are conspicuously missing: ADT objects themselves have no initialization and termination routines (though Modules do), and there are no inheritance relationships. 


In the 90's, an @{" ISO language standard for Modula-2 " LINK "ISO"} was developed and published (ISO/IEC 10154-1) which defined the language in detail, and added a few things without materially changing Modula-2's basic design and elegance. Notably, this included a module @{i}termination @{ui} routine, 
a well defined mechanism for @{i}exception @{ui} trapping and recovery, and a @{" standard IO library " LINK "ISOMods"} that all implementations are expected to provide.


In addition, two standard extensions defining how a language implementer should, if desired, provide an extended language in two areas: One defined language additions to provide true @{b}Object Oriented Modula-2@{ub} (with @{i}classes,@{ui} @{i}inheritance,@{ui} and @{i}garbage collection)@{ui}.
The other was a @{b}Generic Programming Extension@{ub}, to provide template-like modules that still maintain type checking safety.


On the web, check out @{" Modula-2 Links " LINK "M2-Links"}.@{line}
@endnode
@node "M2_Syntax" "M2_Syntax"
@{JRIGHT} Section head: @{"M2 Language" LINK "M2_Language"}@{line}
@{JCENTER}
@{B}Modula-2 Syntax@{UB}

_________________________________________________________________________

@{JLEFT}@{_LMARG_}

The syntax of Modula-2 will be fairly familiar to anyone who knows a bit about Pascal. Like C and Pascal, M2 is a block structured declarative programming language. Unlike them, it was designed from the beginning to support modular programming and information hiding.


The best resource for learning to use Modula-2 is an on-line textbook, "Modula-2: Abstractions for Data and Programming Structures - Modula-2 shareware textbook" by Rick Sutcliffe. This can be found at @{_URL_ "http://www.csc.twu.ca/rsbook"}. 


An explicit specification of the static syntax of M2 is included here: @{" ISO Modula-2 Syntax " LINK "M2Syntax.guide/M2Syntax"}.@{line}

The ISO/IEC 10514-1 document explicitly defining the ISO standard semantics is available, for purchase, from ANSI in the United States, and other ISO organizations elsewhere.


The GNU language backend is currently receiving a mostly ISO compliant Modula-2 front end. Though some differences exist based on its integration with the GNU languages, documentation for this compiler is freely available. (http://www.nongnu.org/gm2/homepage.html)


On the web, check out @{" Modula-2 Links " LINK "M2-Links"}.@{line}
@endnode
@node "ModuleKeys" "Module Consistency"
@{JRIGHT} Section head: @{"M2 Language" LINK "M2_Language"}@{line}
@{JCENTER}
@{B}Module Consistency@{UB}

_________________________________________________________________________

@{JLEFT}@{_LMARG_}

Definition modules are the public interfaces of the units
that are put together to form a M2 program, and Modula-2  will enforce that they be compiled in the order of dependency and modification:@{_SMLDENT_}@{line}

All Definition modules that a Definition module @{_M2_ "IMPORT"}s (ie, that it depends upon) must be compiled before the Definition module itself. Thus, if a Definition module is changed and re-compiled, all compiled modules that depend on (ie, @{_M2_ "IMPORT"}) it need to be re-compiled.@{_LMARG_}@{line}

Any change and re-compile of a Definition module results in a new unique key being stored in the symbol file (#?.SBM) created for this Definition module compilation. Its symbol file also contains the keys of each module that it imports, directly or indirectly.@{line}

So, the compiler can enforce this consistency in Definition modules when they are combined into a program or Implementation module by using the keys to check that all versions for each used Definition module in the #?.SBM files are the same.@{line}

@{_HEADING_ "For Example"}

Given that Definition module @{b}A@{ub} imports Definition modules @{b}B@{ub} and @{b}C@{ub}, and that Definition module @{b}B@{ub} imports @{b}C@{ub}. In the last compile of the following sequence the compiler will detect an consistency error:@{_LRGDENT_}@{line}

Compile @{b}C@{ub}@{line}
Compile @{b}B@{ub}@{line}
Modify @{b}C@{ub}@{line}
Re-compile @{b}C@{ub}@{line}
Compile @{b}A@{ub}     <- error emitted@{_SMLDENT_}@{line}

The compiler will give a "keys of imported symbol files do not match" error. As the public interface of @{b}C@{ub} changed but @{b}B@{ub} was compiled with the old version, you will need to recompile @{b}B@{ub} before the compile of @{b}A@{ub} succeeds.@{_LMARG_}@{line}

@{_HEADING_ "M2IDE"}

The included Integrated Development Environment for @{_AGM2_} automatically determines the correct order of compilation of Definition modules within a project. This can significantly ease the burden on the programmer.@{_LMARG_}@{line}

@{_HEADING_ "Implementation Modules"}

Because the implementation of the module is hidden, in general the order of compilation of Program and Implementation modules does not matter so long as all the Definition modules they use have been compiled appropriately.@{line}

If not, however, @{" link-time inconsistencies " LINK "ModKeysLink"} will show up.@{line}

Another potential problem that may show up at link-time stems from @{" mutual import " LINK "ModKeysCircle"} between two implementation modules during module initialization.@{line}


.
@endnode
@node "ModKeysLink" "ModKeysLink"
@tab 45
@{JRIGHT} Section head: @{"M2 Language" LINK "M2_Language"}@{line}
@{JCENTER}
@{B}Link-time Inconsistency@{UB}

_________________________________________________________________________

@{JLEFT}@{_LMARG_}

For Implementation modules, some import version inconsistencies are not detectable by the compiler, but will be discoverable at
link-time.@{line}

This may occur when the attempt is made to link together two independent Implementation modules which were compiled with different versions of a third Definition module.@{line}

The @{_AGM2_} pre-linker, @{i}Mod2Lnk@{ui}, will detect these and will output information to help you determine which Implementation modules were compiled with the wrong version.@{line}

For example, the following output from a development link of M2IDE, makes it clear that the M2IDE#? and LoggerDefs Implementation modules have not been recompiled with the up-to-date version of AmigaDOS2.def.@{line}

______________________________________________________________________@{_SMLDENT_}@{line}
@{b}
----------------------------@{line}
Module Key Mismatches@{line}
----------------------------@{line}

AmigaDOS2@{line}

     matching clients:@{tab}AmigaDosInterfaces DebugIO SystemRTS Assertions Debugging@{line}
@{tab}OSFile StdChans LocaleInterfaces CharClass ProcessesSupport@{line}
@{tab}SimpleScreens SysClock VirtualTerminal MyTerminal DirUtil2@{line}
@{tab}SimpleRexx DirUtil3 PipeIO ProgramArgs ArgsSupport@{line}
@{tab}TextDisplays@{line}

     mismatching clients:@{tab}M2IDErun M2IDEutils M2IDEapi LoggerDefs@{line}
@{ub}
@endnode
@node "ModKeysCircle" "ModKeysCircle"
@{JRIGHT} Prev section: @{"M2 Language" LINK "M2_Language"}@{line}
@{JCENTER}
@{B}Circular Import Inconsistency@{UB}

_________________________________________________________________________

@{JLEFT}@{_LMARG_}

@{i}Mod2Lnk @{ui} will arrange the order of initialization of a program's modules such that when a module's init code is called, it can assume that the init code for all modules that it @{_M2_ "IMPORT"}s will already have been called.@{line}

However, if two Implementation modules each import from the other's Definition module, this is not possible, and
there may be a problem.@{line}

The problem occurs when the interdependent procedures in question rely on their module's initialization section to have been already executed in order to give correct results, and the call to the procedure occurs during program initialization time.@{line}

Usually, this requires a direct call from init code in one of the modules to a initialization-sensitive procedure in the other module, however, indirect circularity can exist and be difficult to detect.@{line}

The compiler cannot detect this situation, but the pre-linker currently can at least find all Implementation modules that
mutually import each others Definition modules and emit a warning that the error is possible. 

Note that this is only a @{i}warning @{ui}. The use of circular imports which @{i}aren't @{ui} dependent on module initialization order are not a problem.@{line}

For example, @{i}Mod2Lnk@{ui} could output:
@{_SMLDENT_}@{line}

Warning MutualImport: IOLink IOChan@{line}
Warning MutualImport: SimpleGUIHidden SimpleGUI@{line}
Warning MutualImport: SimpleGUISupport SimpleGUI@{_LMARG_}@{line}

The programmer has to determine whether or not initialization problems
exist for the reported cases. If you get many of these warnings on a run of @{i}Mod2Lnk @{ui}, it is probably a hint that the design of your partition of the program into modules may not be ideal.@{line}
@{jcenter}

@{b}NOTE:@{ub} Circular imports among Definition@{line} modules @{i}@{b}are @{ub}@{ui} a language @{i}@{b}error @{ub}@{ui} and will be@{line} detected as such by the compiler.@{line}
@{_LMARG_}@{line}
@endnode
@node "InitTerm" "InitTerm"
@{JRIGHT} Section head: @{"M2 Language" LINK "M2_Language"}@{line}
@{JCENTER}
@{B}Module Initializations and Terminations@{UB}@{line}
_________________________________________________________________________@{line}
@{JLEFT}@{_LMARG_}

As specified in the new ISO standard for Modula-2, any module now can have a code section to be executed on program termination, in addition to the one for initialization.@{line}

The module body code now can be divided into two sections, the first containing the initialization code and the second the termination code. A new language symbol, @{_M2_ "FINALLY"}, was introduced to mark the beginning of the termination code.@{line}

Termination code will be called at program exit no matter what the reason for ending the program: end of main module body, a HALT, or a trapped exception.@{line}

Modules' termination codes will be called in the opposite order from which their initialization codes were called.@{line}

A module's termination code is called only once. A @{_M2_ "HALT"} or exception within its termination code will end that one and continue with the next module's termination code.@{line}

If program exit occurs during initialization before the main module is reached, modules whose  initialization code has not been entered will not be terminated. This implementation will always call termination code, if any, for modules that have no initialization code at all.@{line}

The standard system module TERMINATION is supported as a "built-in" standard module. Its has two procedures:@{lindent 20}@{line}

@{_M2_ "PROCEDURE IsTerminating():BOOLEAN;"}@{line}
@{_M2_ "PROCEDURE HasHalted():BOOLEAN;"}@{line}
@endnode
@node "Exceptions" "Exceptions"
@{JRIGHT} Section head: @{"M2 Language" LINK "M2_Language"}@{line}
@{JCENTER}
@{B}Exceptions Support@{UB}@{line}
_________________________________________________________________________@{line}
@{JLEFT}@{_LMARG_}

The general exception model allows an @{_M2_ "EXCEPT"} section at the end of module init sections, module term sections, and procedure bodies.@{line}

Upon an exception, control transfers to the start of the last activated @{_M2_ "EXCEPT"} block. An exception block becomes activated when its associated code block is entered, and deactivated on the code block exit.@{line}

A @{_M2_ "RETRY"} statement within the exception block will clear the exception status and restart the procedure (or module init/term code) from the beginning.@{line}

A @{_M2_ "RETURN"} statement within the exception block will clear the exception status and exit from the procedure or module body.@{line}

If neither statement is executed within the exception block (ie. the processing "runs off the end"), the exception state remains raised and the previously active exception block is entered. If there is none, the program ends via the system default exception handler.@{line}

Some exceptions are pre-defined since they are specified in one of the Standard ISO Modules. User written modules can also define their own exceptions via the standard module @{b}EXCEPTIONS@{ub}. User defined exceptions are sent to the exception handler cascade by a call to the EXCEPTIONS.Raise() procedure.@{line}

In addition, there are a set of "language exceptions" raised by the operating system or by run-time checks inserted by the compiler. Standard module @{b}M2EXCEPTION@{ub} defines an enumeration of these so that they can be handled, if desired, in your module's EXCEPT section:@{lindent 15}@{line}

@{b}
(indexException, rangeException, caseSelectException, invalidLocation, functionException, wholeValueException, wholeDivException,  realValueException, realDivException, complexValueException, complexDivException, protException, sysException, coException, exException)@{ub}
@{line}
@{_LMARG_}

The compiler switches "-rngchk" and "-ovflchk" also determine whether most of the language exception situations will be detected at run time.@{line}
@{par}
@endnode
@node "ISO" "ISO"
@tab 65
@{JRIGHT} Section head: @{"M2 Language" LINK "M2_Language"}@{line}
@{JCENTER}
@{B}ISO Modula-2 Standard@{UB}

_________________________________________________________________________


@{JLEFT}@{_LMARG_}

The best resource for learning to use ISO Modula-2 is an on-line textbook, "Modula-2: Abstractions for Data and Programming Structures - Modula-2 shareware textbook" by Rick Sutcliffe. This can be found at @{_URL_ "http://www.csc.twu.ca/rsbook"}. 


@{" ISO Modula-2 Syntax " LINK "M2Syntax.guide/M2Syntax"}@{line}

Implemented Features in @{_AGM2_}@{_SMLDENT_}@{line}

- @{" Module Termination " LINK "InitTerm"} @{tab}- the @{_M2_ "FINALLY"} block

- @{" Exceptions " LINK "Exceptions"} @{tab}- the @{_M2_ "EXCEPT"} block

- @{_M2_ "FOR"} loop semantics @{tab}- index variable must be local & unthreatened

- @{_M2_ "LENGTH"} function@{tab}- for null delimited strings

- @{_M2_ "CAST()"} and @{_M2_ "VAL()"} differences@{tab}- Type transfer "functions" removed

- @{_M2_ "SYSTEM.ADDADR()" and @{_M2_ "SUBADR()"}.

- Storage module semantics @{tab}- ALLOCATE failure returns NIL, not an exception

- @{" ISO Standard Modules " LINK "ISOMods"}@{line}
@{_LMARG_}

Not (yet) Implemented in @{_AGM2_}

@{_SMLDENT_}

- Structured type constructors

- Multidimensional open arrays

- Dynamic modules

- @{_M2_ "COROUTINES"} module

- @{_M2_ "COMPLEX"} Type

@{PARD}
@endnode
@node "ISOMods" "ISO Libraries"
@tab 45
@{JRIGHT} Section head: @{"M2 Language" LINK "M2_Language"}@{line}
 Section head: @{"Aglet Implementation" LINK "Aglet_Implementation"}@{line}
@{JCENTER}
@{B}ISO Standard Libraries@{UB}

_________________________________________________________________________

@{JLEFT}@{_LMARG_}


The @{_AGM2_} implementation of these ISO standard modules was based on a
a set of sources provided (and programmed) by
Richard Sutcliffe, Trinity Western University, BC Canada
(Portions coded by G. Tischer).
I am extremely grateful for his contribution.


Thanks to the WG13 and ISO/CS in Geneva, for making the text of all the definition
modules in the standard available.


@{b}Built-In Language Modules@{ub}

   SYSTEM@{line}
   TERMINATION@{line}
   EXCEPTIONS@{line}
   M2EXCEPTION@{line}

@{b}StdIO Library - Logical Device (Channel) Access@{ub}

     SeqFile@{tab}Rewindable sequential files@{line}
     StreamFile@{tab}Independent sequential data streams@{line}
     RndFile@{tab}Random access files@{line}
     TermFile@{tab}The console device@{line}
     ProgramArgs@{tab}Program arguments as an IO channel@{line}

@{B}StdIO Library - Channel Input/Output@{UB}

     TextIO@{tab}Character and line IO@{line}
     WholeIO@{tab}Integer and cardinal IO@{line}
     RealIO@{tab}Real number IO@{line}
     LongIO@{tab}Long real number IO@{line}
     RawIO@{tab}Byte buffer IO@{line}

@{B}StdIO Library - Errors and Result Codes@{UB}

     ChanConsts@{tab}Open modes and open results on channels@{line}
     IOConsts@{tab}Read operation result codes@{line}
     IOResult@{tab}ReadResult() procedure@{line}

@{B}StdIO Library - Standard Channel Input/Output@{UB}

     STextIO@{tab}As above, but the channel is implied.@{line}
     SWholeIO@{tab}"@{line}
     SRealIO@{tab}"@{line}
     SLongIO@{tab}"@{line}
     SRawIO@{tab}"@{line}
     SIOResult@{tab}"@{line}
     StdChans@{tab}Set and get the actual channel used for Standard IO@{line}

@{B}StdIO Library - Device/Channel Association@{UB}

     IOChan@{tab}Lower level channel operations, channel exceptions@{line}
     IOLink@{tab}Channel architecture for device association@{line}

@{B}Strings Library@{UB}

     Strings@{tab}Comparison, extraction, insertion, deletion@{line}
     CharClass@{tab}Numeric, letter, control, whitespace@{line}

@{B}High Level Conversions@{UB}

     WholeStr@{tab}Integer/Cardinal to and from string@{line}
     RealStr@{tab} "   for Real, with float, fixed, engineering formatting@{line}
     ConvTypes@{tab}Conversion error codes@{line}

@{B}Low Level Conversions@{UB}

     WholeConv@{tab}Useful for constructing conversion routines on Int/Card@{line}
     RealConv@{tab} "  for Reals@{line}
     LongConv@{tab} "  for Long Reals@{line}

@{B}Math Library@{UB}

     RealMath@{tab}Trig, log, square root, rounding functions   (uses @{" C libm " LINK "CLIB"})@{line}
     LongMath@{tab}  "  for LONGREAL@{line}
     LowReal@{tab}Access to underlying properties of the REAL type@{line}
     LowLong@{tab} "  for LONGREAL@{line}

@{B}Multiprogramming/Threading@{UB}

   Processes@{tab}Implemented via AmigaDOS Processes@{line}
   Semaphores@{tab}Provides mutual exclusion facilities for processes@{line}
   Coroutines@{tab}<not yet implemented>@{line}

@{B}Etc@{UB}

     SysClock@{tab}Access to current date and time@{line}

-
@endnode
@node "ISOExamples" "ISOExamples"
@tab 10
@{JRIGHT} Section head: @{"M2 Language" LINK "M2_Language"}@{line}
@{JCENTER}
@{B}ISO Examples@{UB}

_________________________________________________________________________

@{JLEFT}@{_LMARG_}

@{" > " LINK "ISO_Exam1"}@{tab}Open an existing text file for reading@{tab}@{line}
@{tab}Read a text file@{line}

@{" > " LINK "ISO_Exam2"}@{tab}Create a new file "safely"@{line}
@{tab}Create a new file "destructively"@{line}

@{" > " LINK "ISO_Exam3"}@{tab}Open an existing binary file to read it@{line}
@{tab}Read a binary sequential file@{line}

@{" > " LINK "ISO_Exam4"}@{tab}Open an existing random-access file for binary reading@{line}
@{tab}Open or Create a random-access file for binary read/write@{line}
@endnode
@node "ISO_Exam1" "ISO_Exam1"
@{JRIGHT} Section head: @{"ISO Examples" LINK "ISOExamples"}@{line}
@{SETTABS 20 45}@{JCENTER}
@{B}ISO Examples-1@{UB}

_________________________________________________________________________

@{JLEFT}@{_LMARG_}
@{code}
@{_HEADING_ "Open an existing text file to read it"}@{_SMLDENT_}@{b}
_________________________________________________________________________
| FROM IOChan  IMPORT ChanId;
| FROM ChanConsts IMPORT ChanFlags, FlagSet, OpenResults;
| FROM SeqFile IMPORT OpenRead;
|
| VAR f  :ChanId;
|  oRes  :OpenResults;
|  @{ub}...@{b}
| OpenRead(f, "MyDev:MyPath/MyFile.ext", FlagSet{}, oRes);
| IF oRes <> opened THEN
|    @{ub}<error processing>@{b}
|  @{ub}...@{b}
|________________________________________________________________________@{ub}
@{_LMARG_}
@{_HEADING_ "Read a text file"}@{_SMLDENT_}
See Aglet support module @{" TextIOHelper " LINK "TextIOHelper"} as well.
@{b}_________________________________________________________________________
| FROM IOConsts   IMPORT ReadResults;
| FROM IOResult   IMPORT ReadResult;
| FROM TextIO  IMPORT ReadString, SkipLine;
| 
| VAR OneLine  :Str0.String132;
|  rRes  :ReadResults;
|  @{ub}...@{b}
| ReadString(f, OneLine);
| rRes := ReadResult(f);    
| WHILE rRes # endOfInput DO 
|    IF rRes = endOfLine THEN
|       SkipLine(f);
|    ELSE
|       Assert(rRes = allRight, "Error encountered reading text file");
|       @{ub}<process the OneLine>@{b}
|       ReadString(f, OneLine);
|    END;
|    rRes := ReadResult(f);
| END;
|________________________________________________________________________
@{ub}
@endnode
@node "ISO_Exam2" "ISO_Exam2"
@{JRIGHT} Section head: @{"ISO Examples" LINK "ISOExamples"}@{line}
@{JCENTER}
@{B}ISO Examples-2@{UB}

_________________________________________________________________________

@{JLEFT}@{_LMARG_}
@{code}
@{_HEADING_ "Create a text file, erroring if there is an existing file of that name"}@{_SMLDENT_}
@{b}_________________________________________________________________________
| FROM IOChan  IMPORT ChanId;
| FROM ChanConsts IMPORT ChanFlags, FlagSet, OpenResults;
| FROM SeqFile IMPORT OpenRead;
|
| VAR f  :ChanId;
|  oRes  :OpenResults;
|  @{ub}...@{b}
| OpenWrite(f, "MyDev:MyPath/MyFile.ext", FlagSet{}, oRes);
| IF oRes <> opened THEN
|    @{ub}<error processing>@{b}
|  @{ub}...@{b}
|________________________________________________________________________@{ub}
@{_LMARG_}
@{_HEADING_ "Create a text file, deleting any existing file of that name"}@{_SMLDENT_}@{b}
_________________________________________________________________________
| FROM IOChan  IMPORT ChanId;
| FROM ChanConsts IMPORT ChanFlags, FlagSet, OpenResults;
| FROM SeqFile IMPORT OpenRead;
|
| VAR f  :ChanId;
|  oRes  :OpenResults;
|  @{ub}...@{b}
| OpenWrite(f, "MyDev:MyPath/MyFile.ext", FlagSet{oldFlag}, oRes);
| IF oRes <> opened THEN
|    @{ub}<error processing>@{b}
|  @{ub}...@{b}
|________________________________________________________________________@{ub}
@{_LMARG_}
@endnode
@node "ISO_Exam3" "ISO_Exam3"
@{JRIGHT} Section head: @{"ISO Examples" LINK "ISOExamples"}@{line}
@{JCENTER}
@{B}ISO Examples-3@{UB}

_________________________________________________________________________

@{JLEFT}@{_LMARG_}
@{code}
@{_HEADING_ "Open an existing binary sequential file to read it"}@{_SMLDENT_}@{b}
_________________________________________________________________________
| FROM IOChan  IMPORT ChanId;
| FROM ChanConsts IMPORT ChanFlags, FlagSet, OpenResults;
| FROM SeqFile IMPORT OpenRead;
|
| VAR f  :ChanId;
|  oRes  :OpenResults;
|  @{ub}...@{b}
| OpenRead(f, "MyDev:MyPath/MyFile.ext", FlagSet{rawFlag}, oRes);
| IF oRes <> opened THEN
|    @{ub}<error processing>@{b}
|  @{ub}...@{b}
|________________________________________________________________________@{ub}
@{_LMARG_}
@{_HEADING_ "Read a binary sequential file"}@{_SMLDENT_}
@{b}_________________________________________________________________________
| FROM IOConsts   IMPORT ReadResults;
| FROM IOResult   IMPORT ReadResult;
| FROM RawIO   IMPORT Read;
|
| TYPE   MyRecords = RECORD Code, Month, Day, Year:CARDINAL END; 
| VAR OneRec   :MyRecords;
|  rRes  :ReadResults;
|  @{ub}...@{b}
| Read(f, OneRec);
| rRes := ReadResult(f);    
| WHILE rRes # endOfInput DO 
|    IF rRes # allRight THEN
|       @{ub}<process the error>@{b}
|    ELSE
|       @{ub}<process the OneRec>@{b}
|       Read(f, OneRec);
|    END;
|    rRes := ReadResult(f);
| END;
|________________________________________________________________________
@{ub}
@endnode
@node "ISO_Exam4" "ISO_Exam4"
@{JRIGHT} Section head: @{"ISO Examples" LINK "ISOExamples"}@{line}
@{JCENTER}
@{B}ISO Examples-4@{UB}

_________________________________________________________________________

@{JLEFT}@{_LMARG_}
@{code}
@{_HEADING_ "Open an existing random-access file for binary reading"}@{_SMLDENT_}
@{b}_________________________________________________________________________
| FROM IOChan  IMPORT ChanId;
| FROM ChanConsts IMPORT ChanFlags, FlagSet, OpenResults;
| FROM RndFile IMPORT OpenOld;
|
| VAR f  :ChanId;
|  oRes  :OpenResults;
|  @{ub}...@{b}
| OpenOld(f, "MyDev:MyPath/MyFile.ext", FlagSet{}, oRes);
| IF oRes <> opened THEN
|    @{ub}<error processing>@{b}
|  @{ub}...@{b}
|________________________________________________________________________@{ub}
@{_LMARG_}
@{_HEADING_ "Open or Create a random-access file for binary read/write"}@{_SMLDENT_}@{b}
_________________________________________________________________________
| FROM IOChan  IMPORT ChanId;
| FROM ChanConsts IMPORT ChanFlags, FlagSet, OpenResults;
| FROM RndFile IMPORT OpenOld;
|
| VAR f  :ChanId;
|  oRes  :OpenResults;
|  @{ub}...@{b}
| OpenOld(f, "MyDev:MyPath/MyFile.ext", FlagSet{writeFlag+oldFlag}, oRes);
| IF oRes <> opened THEN
|    @{ub}<error processing>@{b}
|  @{ub}...@{b}
|________________________________________________________________________@{ub}
@{_LMARG_}
@endnode
@node "OO_Extensions" "OO_Extensions"
@{JRIGHT} Section head: @{"M2 Language" LINK "M2_Language"}@{line}
@{JCENTER}
@{B}Object-Oriented Extensions@{UB}@{line}
_________________________________________________________________________@{line}@{JLEFT}@{_LMARG_}


ISO also standardized an set of Object Oriented extensions for the base Modula-2 standard.


Hopefully, I will be able to implement these into the compiler classes in the foreseeable future.


In this distribution of @{_AGM2_}, most of the class implementation mechanics are available via use of an accessory standard M2 module, @{" MODULE Obj " LINK "Module_Obj"}. It does implement true object-oriented classes (similar to BOOPSI). Unfortunately, the programmer-required bookkeeping is a bit onerous, and I have used it only in one module, @{" MODULE SimpleGraphics " LINK "SimpleGraphics"}.@{line}
 
@endnode
