@node "CLI_Tutorial" "CLI_Tutorial"
@{JRIGHT} Prev section: @{"Modula-2 Language" LINK "M2_Language"}@{line}
 Next section: @{"Aglet Implementation" LINK "Aglet_Implementation"}@{line}
@{JCENTER}
@{B}Command Line Tutorial@{UB}

_________________________________________________________________________@{line}
@{JLEFT}@{_LMARG_}

The general procedure for building a program via the CLI interface is to iterate through the following process:@{_SMLDENT_}@{line}

> Design your program, using existing support Modules and/or constructing new Definition Modules for the major program components.@{line}

> Write the main program Module.@{line}

> Write the Implementation modules for the new Definition modules you have designed and written.@{line}

> Compile these Definition modules.@{line}

> Compile your main Program module and all your new Implementation modules.@{line} 

> Link the program, eg,  "mod2lnk MyProgram"@{_LMARG_}@{line}
_________________________________________________________________________@{line}

@{b}Note:@{ub} Definition modules must be compiled in the logical order: all Definition modules that a Definition module @{_M2_ "IMPORT"}s (ie, that it depends upon) must be compiled before the Definition module itself. (Using @{i}M2IDE @{ui} instead of the CLI to build your package will help with this requirement.)@{line}

Any change and re-compile of a Definition module results in a new unique key being assigned to the symbol file (#?.SBM) created during compilation.@{line}

By reading these files, the compiler will check the Definition module dependencies, direct and indirect, of your program and all its @{_M2_ "IMPORT"}ed modules. It will declare an error if it finds the dependency tree contains more than one version of the same Definition module (ie, Definition modules were not compiled in the correct order).@{line}

In general, the order of compilation of Program and Implementation modules does not matter, but see @{" Module Consistency " LINK "ModuleKeys"} for details on exceptions to this.@{line}
_________________________________________________________________________@{line}
@endnode
@node "SimpleCLI_Pgm" "SimpleCLI_Pgm"
@{JRIGHT} Section Head: @{"Command Line Tutorial" LINK "CLI_Tutorial"}@{line}
@{JCENTER}
@{B}A Simple CLI-Built Example@{UB}

_________________________________________________________________________@{line}
@{JLEFT}@{_LMARG_}

@{_HEADING_ "Write your module source"}
@{lindent 4}

Let's start with the time-honored example, but leave out a parenthesis in order to make the compile more interesting. 
@{" Hello World (err) " LINK "HelloWorld_err"}@{line}@{_LMARG_}

@{_HEADING_ "Compile the module"}
@{lindent 4}

Open a Shell window and invoke the compiler on your source program. You should get compilation messages that look similar to the below.
@{lindent 15}@{line}
_______________________________________________________@{line}
|@{line}
| > @{b}mod2 HelloWorld.mod@{ub}@{line}
|@{line}
| Aglet PPC Mod2 v3.1 Compiler Beta1 (13.2.2011)@{line}
| Copyright (c) 2004 by Thomas Breeden@{line}
|@{line}
| HelloWorld.mod@{line}
|  <- M2Lv3:STextIO.SBM @{line}
|@{line}
|     >>Errors in Source File!@{line}
|______________________________________________________@{line}@{lindent 4}

Run the M2Err program to see the error messages.@{lindent 15}@{line}
_______________________________________________________@{line}
|@{line}
| > @{b}m2err@{ub}@{line}
| M2Err Copyright © 2004 Tom Breeden@{line}
| LIST OF ERRORS FOUND IN FILE: HelloWorld.mod@{line}
| WriteString("Hello world!";      (* missing parenthesis *)@{line}
|@{fg Background} WriteString("Hello world!"@{fg Text}^@{line}
| line: 10  err: 015 )  right parenthesis expected@{line}
|______________________________________________________@{line}
@{_LMARG_}

@{" Next " LINK "Simple_CLI2"} (Fix and re-Compile the module)@{line}
@endnode
@node "Simple_CLI2" "Simple_CLI2"
@{JRIGHT} Section Head: @{"Command Line Tutorial" LINK "CLI_Tutorial"}@{line}
@{JCENTER}
@{B}A Simple CLI-Built Example@{UB}, continued

_________________________________________________________________________@{line}
@{JLEFT}@{_LMARG_}

@{_HEADING_ "Fix and re-Compile the module"}

Edit the parenthesis into the file at the appropriate point and try again. @{" HelloWorld.mod " LINK "HelloWorld"}@{lindent 15}@{line}
_______________________________________________________@{line}
|@{line}
| > @{b}mod2 HelloWorld@{ub}@{line}
|@{line}
| Aglet PPC Mod2 v3.1 Compiler Beta1 (13.2.2011)@{line}
| Copyright (c) 2004 by Thomas Breeden@{line}
| HelloWorld.mod@{line}
|  <- M2Lv3:STextIO.SBM@{line}
|@{line}
|  -> T:HelloWorld.asm@{line}
|@{line}
| Optimize Setting: DeadCode@{line}
| SDK:gcc/bin/as -o HelloWorld.o T:HelloWorld.asm 0@{line}
|______________________________________________________@{line}
@{lindent 4}

This time the compiler successfully creates the PPC assembly language file and invokes the SDK program @{i}as @{ui} to produce the Elf object file.@{line}@{_LMARG_}

@{" Next " LINK "Simple_CLI3"} (Link the Program Module)@{line}
@endnode
@node "Simple_CLI3" "Simple_CLI3"
@next "Aglet_Implementation"
@{JRIGHT} Section Head: @{"Command Line Tutorial" LINK "CLI_Tutorial"}@{line}
@{JCENTER}
@{B}A Simple CLI-Built Example@{UB}, continued

_________________________________________________________________________@{line}
@{JLEFT}@{_LMARG_}

@{_HEADING_ "Link the Program Module"}

_______________________________________________________@{line}
|@{line}
| > @{b}mod2lnk HelloWorld@{ub}@{line}
| Mod2Lnk Amiga 0.4 (16.12.2009) OS 4.0 Beta2@{line}
| Copyright (c) 2004 Tom Breeden@{line}
| @{line}
| HelloWorld@{line}
| SDK:gcc/bin/as -o HelloWorld_start.o HelloWorld_start.asm@{line}
| SDK:gcc/bin/ld -o HelloWorld T:HelloWorld.lnk -q -nostdlib -x@{line}
| Mod2Lnk done@{line}
|______________________________________________________@{line}
@{lindent 4}

The M2 pre-linker has inspected the HelloWorld.o file, which contains a summary of the program Module's imports, found the standard IO module STextIO and continued recursively to determine all the modules that must be linked for this program.@{line}

It created and assembled the startup object module for this program.@{line}

And finally it put together the a command file for the SDK linker and invoked @{i}ld @{ui} to produce the executable, HelloWorld.@{line}@{_LMARG_}

@{_HEADING_ "Run the Program"}@{line}
_______________________________________________________@{line}
|@{line}
| > @{b}HelloWorld@{ub}@{line}
| Hello world!@{line}
| Goodbye world@{line}
|______________________________________________________@{line}
@{lindent 4}

@{" Run It " SYSTEM "HelloWorld > CON:10/10/200/100/HelloWorld/CLOSE/WAIT "}@{line}
@endnode
@node "HelloWorld_err" "HelloWorld_err"
@prev "SimpleCLI_Pgm"
@next "SimpleCLI_Pgm"
@{_LMARG_}
@{code}
(*############*)
 MODULE HelloWorld;                     (* $VER: HelloWorld.mod 0.0 (13.3.2008) *)
(*############*)

FROM STextIO  IMPORT WriteLn, WriteString;

BEGIN

WriteString("Hello world!";             (* missing parenthesis *)
WriteLn;

FINALLY

WriteString("Goodbye world"); WriteLn;

END HelloWorld.           
@endnode
@node "HelloWorld" "HelloWorld"
@next "Simple_CLI2"
@prev "Simple_CLI2"
@{JLEFT}^CLI_Tutorial@{line}
@{_LMARG_}
@{code}
(*############*)
 MODULE HelloWorld;                     (* $VER: HelloWorld.mod 0.0 (13.3.2008) *)
(*############*)

FROM STextIO  IMPORT WriteLn, WriteString;

BEGIN

WriteString("Hello world!");                    (* missing parenthesis fixed here *)
WriteLn;

FINALLY

WriteString("Goodbye world"); WriteLn;

END HelloWorld.           
@endnode
@node "Aglet_Implementation" "Aglet_Implementation"
@tab 45
@prev "Simple_CLI3"
@{JRIGHT} Prev section: @{"Command Line Tutorial" LINK "CLI_Tutorial"}@{line}
 Next section: @{"Example Programs" LINK "M2_Examples"}@{line}
@{JCENTER}@{B}@{I}@{FG Highlight}A@{FG Text}@{UI}glet Implementation@{UB}@{_LMARG_}@{line}

@{JLEFT}

M2 Compiler@{TAB}@{" > " LINK "Compiler"}@{line}
Obj File Linking@{TAB}@{" > " LINK "Linker"}@{line}
Tools@{TAB}@{" > " LINK "Tools"}@{line}

Aglet Support Modules@{TAB}@{" > " LINK "Support"}@{line}

Amiga Specific Info@{tab}@{" > " LINK "Amiga_Specific"}@{line}
