Debugging Hints@{TAB}@{" > " LINK "Debugging"}@{line}

.
@endnode
@node "Compiler" "Compiler"
@tab 3
@{JRIGHT} Section Head: @{"Aglet Implementation" LINK "Aglet_Implementation"}@{line}
@{JCENTER}
@{B}M2 Compiler@{UB}

_________________________________________________________________________

@{JLEFT}@{_LMARG_}

The compiler version documented here is:

Aglet M2 PPC Compiler v3.1 Beta Compiler (13.2.2011)

Copyright (c) 2004 by Tom Breeden


@{"Compiler Switches" LINK "Compiler-Switches"}@{line}
@{_SMLDENT_}

All switches start with a dash.

@{_LMARG_}

@{"Embedded Switches" LINK "Compiler-Pragmas"}@{line}
@{_SMLDENT_}

All  Pragmas (embedded switches) are delimited by the "@{b}<*@{ub}" and "@{b}*>@{ub}" characters, similar to a "special" comment.
@{_LMARG_}@{line}

@{"Amiga Library Calls" LINK "ALIB"}
@{_SMLDENT_}@{line}
@{_LMARG_}

@{"Library Auto-Open" LINK "LibAutoOpen"}
@{LINDENT 3}@{line}

The startup code always opens the five libraries dos, graphics, intuition, and layers.

Nearly all other modules that provide access to an Amiga shared library will open that library, and its main Interface, in the module initialization code (and close it in the termination code), so you will rarely call OpenLibrary in your code.

@{_LMARG_}

@{"Static C Library Calls" LINK "CLIB"}

@{_LMARG_}

@{u}Other compiler info@{uu}
@{_SMLDENT_}@{line}

1. A null char is placed at end of every literal string.@{line}
2. @{lindent 12}An embedded PPC assembler is provided, but it is very "bare-bones", and probably of little use except for very specialized requirements (eg, non-ABI calls).@{_SMLDENT_}@{line}
@{_LMARG_}@{line}
@{" SYSTEM module " LINK "SYSTEM.def"}@{line}

@{" Type low-level information and extensions " LINK "LowLevel"}@{line}

@{_LMARG_}



.
@endnode
@node "Compiler-Switches" "Compiler-Switches"
@tab 35
@{JRIGHT} Section Head: @{"M2 Compiler" LINK "Compiler"}@{line}
@{JCENTER}
@{B}Compiler Switches@{UB}

_________________________________________________________________________

@{JLEFT}@{_LMARG_}

@{_HEADING_ "Runtime Checking Control "}

@{b}-rngchk@{ub}@{tab}Range Chk = checks of indexing, subrange, implied type conversions.@{line}
@{b}-rngchkoff@{ub}@{tab}Compile without generating any range checks.@{line}
@{b}-ovflchk@{ub}@{tab}Overflow Chk = checks of arithmetic operations.@{line}
@{b}-ovflchkoff@{ub}@{tab}Compile without generating any overflow checks.@{_LMARG_}@{line}

@{_HEADING_ "Code Generation Control "}

@{b}-nocode@{ub}@{tab}Parse and produce intermediate code, but skip generating PPC code.@{line}
@{b}-optlev@{ub} <num>@{tab}Optimize Level (currently not needed as there is only one level)@{line}
@{b}-debugopt@{ub}@{tab}Does a compile with very little optimization.@{_LMARG_}@{line}

@{_HEADING_ "Debugging and Information "}

@{b}-list@{ub}@{tab}Output a source + code listing@{line}
@{b}-listfil@{ub} <str>@{tab}Write the listing to this file@{line}
@{b}-verbose@{ub}@{tab}Verbose compile, reporting on each phase of the compile.@{line}
@{b}-verbose+@{ub}@{tab}More Verbose compile@{_LMARG_}@{line}

@{_HEADING_ "Import and Output Control "}

@{b}-infil@{ub} <str>@{tab}Input file specification@{line}
@{b}-outdir@{ub} <str>@{tab}Out Files Dir  (for the sym and obj files, #?.asm files are always written to T:)@{line}
@{b}-symdir@{ub} <str>@{tab}Sym Files Dir   - "M2Lv3:" will always be searched as well.@{_LMARG_}@{line}

@{_HEADING_ "Settings of compiler resource sizes "}

@{b}-instrubuf@{ub} <num>@{tab}@{lindent 43}Instruction Buffer size - very large procedures may require more than the default.@{_LMARG_}@{line}

The Amiga program template looks like this:@{_SMLDENT_}@{line}

-infil,-symdir/K,-outdir/K,-nocode/S,-optlev/K/N,-rngchk/S,-rngchkoff/S,@{line}
-ovflchk/S,-ovflchkoff/S,-stkchk/S,-instrubuf/K/N,@{line}
-list/S,-listfil/K,-pragma/K,-verbose/S,-verbose+/S,@{line}
-debugopt/S,-debug/S,-wdebug/S,-dbgverbose/S,@{line}
-dbgverbose+/S,-todo/S,-clrkey/S,-version/S,-help/S@{_LMARG_}@{line}

Defaults if no switches are given are:@{_SMLDENT_}@{line}

-rngchk -ovflchk -instrubuf 5000@{_LMARG_}@{line}

.
@endnode
@node "Compiler-Pragmas" "Compiler-Pragmas"
@tab 36
@{JRIGHT} Section Head: @{"M2 Compiler" LINK "Compiler"}@{line}
@{settabs 45}
@{JCENTER}
@{B}Compiler Pragmas@{UB}@{line}
_________________________________________________________________________


@{JLEFT}@{_LMARG_}

<*@{b}ISOMode@{ub}()*>@{tab}Strict, Semi, or Loose - eg <*ISOMode(Semi)*>@{line}
<*@{b}AlignMode@{ub}()*>@{tab}SysV, Amiga or Default@{line}
<*@{b}NoParamCopy@{ub}()*>@{tab}ON or OFF@{line}
<*@{b}ForeignProc@{ub}()*>@{tab}ON or OFF@{line}
<*@{b}Asm@{ub}()*>@{tab}ON or OFF@{line}
<*@{b}PrologOff@{ub}()*>@{tab}ON or OFF@{line}
<*@{b}PostlogOff@{ub}()*>@{tab}ON or OFF@{line}
<*@{b}RangeCheck@{ub}()*>@{tab}ON or OFF@{line}
<*@{b}OverflowCheck@{ub}()*>@{tab}ON or OFF@{line}
_________________________________________________________________________@{settabs 30}@{line}

@{b}NOTES:@{ub}@{line}

1. @{u}ISOMode@{uu}@{_SMLDENT_}@{line}
Strict   - Any non-ISO compliant usage is flagged as an error.@{line}
Semi  - Allows ADR() on string literals@{_SMLDENT_}@{line}
Loose - Allows ADR() on a lev 0 procedures.@{_SMLDENT_}@{line}
   -@{_HGHDENT_} HIGH() on non-open arrays@{_SMLDENT_}@{line}
   - Interprets quoted \\n, \\b, \\r, \\t, \\f, \\v, \\xNN \\NNN@{_SMLDENT_}
@{_LMARG_}@{line}

2. @{u}AlignMode@{uu}@{_SMLDENT_}@{line}
Needed for most existing AmigaLib structure definitions, which are mapped to memory differently from the PPC SysV alignment rules. New code, if it does not require M68K compatibility, can use the default of SysV alignment.
@{_LMARG_}@{line}

3. @{u}NoParamCopy@{uu}@{_SMLDENT_}@{line}
Forces off any copying of non-@{_M2_ "VAR"} dynamic arrays. The compiler only makes a copy of these pass-by-value parameters if the procedure actually changes or "threatens" the parameter. In programming for a C based API like Amiga's
this usually is due to having to use the ADR() function to pass a string pointer. Documentation should be consulted to determine if
the called routine actually changes the string.@{line}

Careful, do not use this unless you are sure the array is not changed.
@{_LMARG_}@{line}

4. @{u}Asm@{uu}@{_SMLDENT_}@{line}
Bracket embedded PPC assembly code with @{b}<*Asm(ON)*>@{ub} / @{b}<*Asm(OFF)*>@{ub}.@{_LMARG_}@{line}

5. @{u}ForeignProc@{uu}@{_SMLDENT_}@{line}
Procedures declared in the Definition module while @{b}<*ForeignProc(ON)*>@{ub} are not present in the Implementation
module. e.g, the procs in libm.def, which are linked in from the SDK's C library "clib2/lib/libm.a".
@{_LMARG_}@{line}                                                 

6. @{u}PrologOff/PostlogOff@{uu}@{_SMLDENT_}@{line}
Special usage, perhaps with <*Asm(ON)*>.
@{_LMARG_}@{line}

                                                 
@endnode
@node "ALIB" "ALIB"
@tab 35
@{JRIGHT} Section Head: @{"M2 Compiler" LINK "Compiler"}@{line}
@{JCENTER}
@{B}Amiga Library Calls@{UB}

_________________________________________________________________________

@{JLEFT}@{_LMARG_}

Amiga library @{b}Interfaces@{ub} are represented in @{_AGM2_} as pointers to a record each field of which represents, and is named for, one of the functions defined in the interface's XML specification.@{line}

The first parameter, always the interface pointer itself, is not hidden. Varargs versions of the functions are not supported, but are represented in the Interface table structure simply by dummy @{_M2_ "PROC"} entries.@{line}

These records are defined in Definition modules distributed with @{_AGM2_}, generally named by appending "Interfaces" to the name of the Amiga library. The Interface pointer, which is autoopened in the module initialization code, is also declared in this Definition module, ready-to-use.@{line}

For example, to call the AmigaDos library Open routine, use:@{_SMLDENT_}@{line}

f := IDOS^.Open(IDOS, "MyFile", ModeOldFile);@{_LMARG_}@{line}

Here is part of the AmigaDosInterfaces.def file:@{line}
_________________________________________________________________________@{_SMLDENT_}@{line}

(*################################*)@{line}
 @{_M2_ "DEFINITION MODULE"} AmigaDosInterfaces;                                      (* $VER: AmigaDosInterfaces.def 0.0 (21.1.2008) *)@{line}
(*################################*)@{line}
@{_M2_ "FROM"} SYSTEM   @{_M2_ "IMPORT"} ADDRESS, BYTE;@{line}
@{_M2_ "FROM"} Types @{_M2_ "IMPORT"} INTEGER64, STRPTR;@{line}
@{_M2_ "FROM"} Interfaces  @{_M2_ "IMPORT"} InterfaceData, InterfacePtr;@{line}
@{_M2_ "FROM"} AmigaDOS @{_M2_ "IMPORT"} BPTR, BSTR, DateStampPtr, DateStampRecord, FileHandle, FileInfoBlockPtr, <etc> @{b}...@{ub}@{line}

<*AlignMode(SysV)*>@{line}

@{_M2_ "TYPE"} DOSIFacePtr = POINTER TO DOSIFace;@{line}
@{_M2_ "CONST"} dosLibName = "dos.library";@{line}
@{_M2_ "VAR"}   DOSBase   :LibraryPtr;@{line}
         IDOS  :DOSIFacePtr;@{line}
@{_M2_ "TYPE"}@{line}
DOSIFace = @{_M2_ "RECORD"}   (* v1.0 *)@{line}
   Data :InterfaceData;@{line}
   Obtain@{tab}:@{_M2_ "PROCEDURE"}(DOSIFacePtr):@{_M2_ "CARDINAL"};@{line}
   Release@{tab}:@{_M2_ "PROCEDURE"}(DOSIFacePtr):@{_M2_ "CARDINAL"};@{line}
   Expunge@{tab}:@{_M2_ "PROCEDURE"}(DOSIFacePtr);@{line}
   Clone@{tab}:@{_M2_ "PROCEDURE"}(DOSIFacePtr):InterfacePtr;@{line}
   Open@{tab}:@{_M2_ "PROCEDURE"}(DOSIFacePtr, (*name*)@{_M2_ "ARRAY OF CHAR"}, (*accessMode*)@{_M2_ "INTEGER"}):FileHandle;@{line}
   Close@{tab}:@{_M2_ "PROCEDURE"}(DOSIFacePtr, FileHandle):@{_M2_ "INTEGER"};@{line}
   Read@{tab}:@{_M2_ "PROCEDURE"}(DOSIFacePtr, FileHandle, (*buffer*)ADDRESS, (*length*)@{_M2_ "INTEGER"}):@{_M2_ "INTEGER"};@{line}
<etc> @{b}...@{ub}@{_LMARG_}@{line}
_________________________________________________________________________@{line}

See the description of the tool @{" IDLTm2 " LINK "IDLTm2"} for more details on @{_AGM2_}'s support of creating interface Definition module files from the AmigaLibrary's XML Interface specification.@{line}

 
@endnode
@node "LibAutoOpen" "LibAutoOpen"
@{JRIGHT} Section head: @{"M2 Compiler" LINK "Compiler"}@{line}
@{JCENTER}
@{B}Library Auto-Open@{UB}

_________________________________________________________________________

@{JLEFT}@{_LMARG_}

The init code of the library interface Implementation module opens the library and its Main Interface, which is used to make calls to the library. The module's term code closes both.@{line}

For example, for DataTypes we have@{_SMLDENT_}@{line}

@{_M2_ "DEFINITION MODULE"} DataTypesInterfaces;@{line}

   which exports these items:@{line}

@{_M2_ "VAR"} DataTypesBase :LibraryPtr;@{line}
@{_M2_ "TYPE"} DataTypesIFacePtr = @{_M2_ "POINTER TO"} DataTypesIFace;@{line}
@{_M2_ "VAR"} IDataTypes   :DataTypesIFacePtr;@{line}

DataTypesIFace is a @{_M2_ "RECORD"} defining the interfaces's procedures, each as a named field in the record.@{line}

eg,@{line}

NewDTObjectA :@{_M2_ "PROCEDURE"}(DataTypesIFacePtr, (*name*)@{_M2_ "ARRAY OF CHAR"}, @{_M2_ "ARRAY OF"} TagItem):Object;@{line}

which is called as:@{line}

obj @{_M2_ ":="} IDataTypes^.NewDTObjectA(IDataTypes, 'Myfile.guide', TagItems);@{line}  
@endnode
@node "CLIB" "CLIB"
@{JRIGHT} Section head: @{"M2 Compiler" LINK "Compiler"}@{line}
@{JCENTER}
@{B}Static C Library Calls@{UB}

_________________________________________________________________________

@{JLEFT}@{_LMARG_}

The ELF object file format used by the compiler is compatible with that of gcc. You can use C procedures from a static library (that follows the SYSV ABI) as follows:@{_SMLDENT_}@{line}

> Create a Definition module for using use the @{b}<*ForeignProc(ON)*>@{ub} compiler pragma.@{line}

This defines the parameters and return value for M2 use and tells the compiler not to look for any implementation of these procedures in the corresponding Implementation module.@{line}

> Use the @{b}-libname <path/file>@{ub} switch when using @{i}Mod2Lnk @{ui} so that the linker can retrieve the object code for these C functions.
@{_LMARG_}@{line}

(It should also be possible to prepare a static library from a Modula-2 module that can be linked into a C program, but I have done no work with this.)@{line}

Actually, the only static C library I've used so far is SDK:clib2/lib/libm,
which is currently used to implement most of the ISO Standard RealMath library modules.@{line}

eg,
_________________________________________________________________________

@{JLEFT}@{_LMARG_}

(*#################*)@{line}
 @{_M2_ "DEFINITION MODULE"} libm;                    (* $VER: libm.def 0.0 (3.7.2007) *)@{line}
(*#################*)@{line}
(* For calling functions in SDK:clib2/lib/libm.a@{line}
    You will need to use the "-libname" switch in Mod2Lnk as well. *)@{line}

<*ForeignProc(ON)*>@{line}

 @{_M2_ "PROCEDURE"} acos(x:@{_M2_ "LONGREAL"}):@{_M2_ "LONGREAL"};@{line}
 @{_M2_ "PROCEDURE"} asin(x:@{_M2_ "LONGREAL"}):@{_M2_ "LONGREAL"};@{line}
 @{_M2_ "PROCEDURE"} atan(x:@{_M2_ "LONGREAL"}):@{_M2_ "LONGREAL"};@{line}
 @{_M2_ "PROCEDURE"} atan2(y, x:@{_M2_ "LONGREAL"}):@{_M2_ "LONGREAL"};@{line}
 @{_M2_ "PROCEDURE"} ceil(x:@{_M2_ "LONGREAL"}):@{_M2_ "LONGREAL"};@{line}
 @{_M2_ "PROCEDURE"} cos(x:@{_M2_ "LONGREAL"}):@{_M2_ "LONGREAL"};@{line}
 
 <etc> @{b}...@{ub}@{line}
@endnode
@node "SYSTEM.def" "SYSTEM.def"
@tab 35
@{JRIGHT} Section head: @{"M2 Compiler" LINK "Compiler"}@{line}
@{jLEFT}@{_LMARG_}

The pseudo-module SYSTEM is embedded in the compiler, but still must be IMPORTed if
you use its low-level facilities:
@{CODE}

(*######################*)
@{B}DEFINITION MODULE SYSTEM;@{UB}
(*######################*)

@{B}TYPE@{UB}

   BYTE; (* 1 byte *)
   WORD; (* 2 bytes *)
   LONGWORD;   (* 4 bytes *)
   LOC = BYTE;
   ADDRESS = POINTER TO LOC;  (* 4 bytes *)

 @{B}PROCEDURE@{UB} ADR():ADDRESS;
 @{B}PROCEDURE@{UB} TSIZE():CARDINAL;

 @{B}PROCEDURE@{UB} REG([0..31]):CARDINAL;    (* get GPR register contents *)
 @{B}PROCEDURE@{UB} FREG([0..31]):CARDINAL;   (* get FPR register contents *)
 @{b}PROCEDURE@{ub} SREG([0..4]):CARDINAL;    (* get special register, for PPC 0=CR, 1=LR, 2=CTR, 3=XER, 4=FPSCR *)

 @{B}PROCEDURE@{UB} SETREG([0..31], CARDINAL | INTEGER);
 @{B}PROCEDURE@{UB} SETFREG([0..31], );                               (* SETFREG not yet implemented *)
 @{b}PROCEDURE@{ub} SETSREG([0..4], CARDINAL | INTEGER)

 @{b}PROCEDURE@{ub} SHIFT(<packedset type>, <whole var>):<packedset type>;
 @{B}PROCEDURE@{UB} CAST(<type>, <var>):<int32typ>;
 @{B}PROCEDURE@{UB} ADDADR(<addrtyp>, CARDINAL):<addrtyp>;
 @{B}PROCEDURE@{UB} SUBADR(<addrtyp>, CARDINAL):<addrtyp>;
@endnode
@node "LowLevel" "LowLevel"
@tab 45
@{JRIGHT} Section head: @{"M2 Compiler" LINK "Compiler"}@{line}
@{JCENTER}
@{B}Low Level Information@{UB}

_________________________________________________________________________

@{JLEFT}@{_LMARG_}

@{_HEADING_ "Module SystemRTS"}

The Aglet system uses a "hidden" module, SystemRTS, to provide some common run-time code support for every program.@{line}

The compiler embeds calls to some of the SystemRTS routines in generated code in order to implement actions related to procedure prologue and epilog,
most of the EXCEPTION processing support, and other things. The pre-linker uses it for program startup and exit code.@{line}

SystemRTS is a normal module (residing in M2Lv3:system/), and must be accessible during every compile and link. You @{u}do not@{uu} have to explicitly import it for the compiler's usage.@{line}

Currently, however, there are item(s) in its Definition module that you may want to access in your code (eg, a variable containing the CLIReturnCode). In which case, you must explicitly import SystemRTS.@{_LMARG_}@{line}

@{_HEADING_ "Type Sizes"}

BOOLEAN  1 byte     @{line}
CHAR  1 byte     @{line}
CARDINAL 4 bytes     @{line}
INTEGER  4 bytes     @{line}
BITSET8  1 bytes     @{line}
BITSET   2 bytes     @{line}
BITSET32 4 bytes     @{line}
REAL  4 bytes     @{line}
LONGREAL 8 bytes     @{line}
PROC  4 bytes     @{line}
CARDINAL16  2 bytes     @{line}
CARDINAL8   1 byte     @{line}
INTEGER16   2 bytes     @{line}
INTEGER8 1 byte     @{line}

CARDINAL32   = CARDINAL@{line}
INTEGER32    = INTEGER@{line}

Array indices@{tab}1, 2, or 4 bytes, depending on the index type@{line}
Enumerations@{tab}1 byte@{line}
Sets@{tab}1, 2, or 4 bytes, depending of the set size@{_LMARG_}@{line}

@{" PPC SysV ABI Summary " LINK "SYSV"}@{line}

@{u}Module Keys@{uu}@{_LMARG_}@{line}

The module version key is a 32 bit "Fletcher" type
checksum. The extra bits are currently zeroed.@{line}

The checksum is only calculated on significant characters in the DEF file, ie it does not
include spaces or tabs (unless in a literal) or comments, so a DEF file can be reformatted graphically and comments added/changed and it will still
compile to the same key value.   
@endnode
@node "SYSV" "ABI"
@{JRIGHT} Section head: @{"M2 Compiler" LINK "Compiler"}@{line}
@{JCENTER}
@{B}SysV ABI@{UB}

_________________________________________________________________________

@{JLEFT}@{_LMARG_}

@{_HEADING_ "Calling protocol"}

PPC SysV ABI is used for parameters.@{line}
HIGH() values are passed "hidden" from the ABI (available to Modula-2 programs only)@{line}

The Module's global data pointer is maintained in r13.@{line}
The Procedure's mark (frame) data pointer is maintained in r14.@{_LMARG_}@{line}

@{_HEADING_ "PPC SysV ABI Summary"}

Register r1 is used as the stack pointer.@{line}

Most parameters are passed in registers; the first eight non-floating point parameters are assigned to r3..r10 in order left to right. The first seven FP parameters are assign to f2..f8.@{line}

Floating point return values are placed in f1. Other return values into r3, and, if 64 bit, r4.@{line}

Only for registers r13..r31 and f14..f31 will the contents be preserved across procedure calls.@{line}

Any parameters after the eight GP registers (or seven FP registers) are passed in a special area of the caller's stack frame. Each of these parameters is stored extended to 32 bits in that area, except that all Floating Points parameters are converted to Double Precision (64 bits).@{line} 

In general, scaler types are allocated at an address aligned to their size (eg, CHAR is aligned to 1 byte, INTEGER to 4 bytes, REAL to 4 bytes).@{line}

A RECORD is placed in memory at an alignment equal to the largest alignment value of any of its members. An ARRAY is always aligned to the alignment of its elements.@{line}

Details can be found in the document, @{i}SystemV Application Binary Interface, PowerPC Processor Supplement @{ui}, Steve Zucker, Sunsoft and Kari Karhi, IBM - available on-line.@{line}

@{" Stack Frame " LINK "StackFrame"}

.
@endnode
@node "StackFrame" "StackFrame"
@font "Bitstream Vera Sans Mono.font" 12
@{JRIGHT} Section head: @{"M2 Compiler" LINK "Compiler"}@{line}
@{JCENTER}
@{B}Stack Frame@{UB}

_________________________________________________________________________

@{JLEFT}@{_LMARG_}

        FPR Save Area              <varying size> max is 32*8 = 256@{line}
        GPR Save Area              <varying size> max is 32*4 = 128@{line}
        CR Save Area               4 bytes@{line}
        Frame Padding to 16 bytes  <varying size> -------------------,@{line}
        Dyn array pass-by-val copy <varying size>  Modula-2 ---,     |@{line}
        pass-by-value array copy   <varying size>  Modula-2 ---'     |   ABI "Local Variable Area"@{line}
        Local Variable Space       <varying size> -------------,     |@{line}
        for Reg Params and HIGHs   <varying size>  Modula-2    |     |@{line}
        gp save word               4 bytes         Modula-2    |     |@{line}
 mp ->  mp Back Chain              4 bytes         Modula-2 ---' ----'@{line}
        Static Link for Callee     4/0 bytes       Modula-2 ---,@{line}
        ...                                                    |  ABI Parameter Passing Area@{line}
        HIGHs for Callee           n*4 bytes       Modula-2    |@{line}
        ABI Overflow params        <varying size> -------------'@{line}
        LR Save word               4 bytes@{line}
 sp ->  Frame Back Chain           4 bytes@{line}



The stack frame has 16 byte(!) alignment.@{line}

 
@endnode
@node "Linker" "Linker"
@tab 40
@{JRIGHT} Section Head: @{"Aglet Implementation" LINK "Aglet_Implementation"}@{line}
 Next subsection: @{"Tools" LINK "Tools"}@{line}
@{JCENTER}
@{B}Amiga Object File Linking@{UB}

_________________________________________________________________________

@{JLEFT}@{_LMARG_}

@{i}Mod2Lnk @{ui} performs some Modula-2 specific pre-processing and then invokes the @{i}ld @{ui} linker from the Amiga OS4 SDK to produce a standard AOS4 Elf object file. I often refer to @{i}Mod2Lnk @{ui} as the "pre-linker".@{line}

@{_HEADING_ "What Mod2Lnk Does"}

Finds, using the current directory, any command line switches, and the "M2Lv3:" assign, the object files for all directly and indirectly imported modules used by your program.@{line}

Checks for module key @{" link-time inconsistencies " LINK "ModKeysLink"}.@{line}

Warns about @{" mutual dependencies " LINK "ModKeysCircle"} between modules, which may introduce problems due to initialization order.@{line}

Generates an "xxx_start" object file which controls the proper order of module initialization and termination calls.@{line}@{_LMARG_}

@{_HEADING_ "Linker Switches"}

-infil/A@{tab}Name of program module@{line}
-indir/K@{tab}Dir to search for object files ("M2Lv3:" will always be searched)@{line}
-outdir/K@{tab}Where to put the output file@{line}
-stack/K/N@{tab}Stack size to embed in executable via the "$STACK:xxxxxx" string.@{line}
-g=-incldbg/S@{tab}Currently, specified that local proc symbols be included in the executable.@{line}
-verbose/S@{tab}Display a list of all modules linked and the order of module inits/terms@{line}
-verbose+/S@{tab}As above, but also include info on the clients each module has.@{line}
-listfil/K@{tab}Output info to a file rather than stdout@{line}
-libname/K@{tab}Non-M2 obj library to include in the link (eg. "SDK:clib2/lib/libm.a")@{line}
-listmap/K@{tab}Ask ld to produce a link map@{line}
-version/S@{line}
-help/S@{line}@{_LMARG_}

@{_HEADING_ "Example"}
A link of the program @{i}GuideMaker @{ui}:@{line}@{b}
_____________________________________________________@{line}
mod2lnk GuideMaker -libname Work:SDK/clib2/lib/libm.a@{line}

Mod2Lnk Amiga 0.4 (11.7.2009)@{line}
OS 4.0 Copyright (c) 2004 Tom Breeden@{line}

    GuideMaker@{line}
Warning MutualImport: SimpleGUIHidden SimpleGUI@{line}
Warning MutualImport: SimpleGUISupport SimpleGUI@{line}
Warning MutualImport: GuideMakerNodeProcess GuideMakerGUI@{line}

SDK:gcc/bin/as -o GuideMaker_start.o GuideMaker_start.asm@{line}
SDK:gcc/bin/ld -o GuideMaker T:GuideMaker.lnk -q -nostdlib -x@{line}
Mod2Lnk done@{line}
_____________________________________________________@{line}@{ub}

@{line}@{_LMARG_}
@endnode
@node "Tools" "Tools"
@tab 30
