 Next subsection: @{"Aglet Support Module" LINK "Support"}@{line}
@{JCENTER}
@{B}Tools@{UB}

_________________________________________________________________________

@{JLEFT}@{_LMARG_}

@{" M2Err " LINK "M2Err"}@{tab}Error lister@{line}

@{" IDLTm2 " LINK "IDLTm2"}@{tab}Interface XML to Definition module@{line}

@{" TGm2 " LINK "TGm2"}@{tab}Test Generator@{line}
@endnode
@node "M2Err" "M2Err"
@{JRIGHT} Section Head: @{"Tools" LINK "Tools"}@{line}
@{JCENTER}
@{B}M2Err@{UB}

_________________________________________________________________________

@{JLEFT}@{_LMARG_}

The compiler writes out error information for each module compilation into the directory "T:" in binary format and named as <module>".err".


The small program "M2Err" will interpret and list the errors in the .err file. If the source file is accessible to M2Err, it will list the appropriate source line along with each error message.


M2Err template:  -f,-w/S,-p/S


   @{B}-f@{UB}  should be followed by the name of the error file.

   @{B}-p@{UB} causes M2Err to pause between the output of each error.

   @{B}-w@{UB} causes it to open a window and write the error results into it.


If no "-f" parameter is given, it will process the most recently written .err file in T:.

@{_SMLDENT_}

Note: If you use the integrated development environment, @{i}M2IDE @{ui}, you will not need to run @{i}M2Err @{ui} yourself.

@{PARD}
@endnode
@node "IDLTm2" "IDLTm2"
@tab 30
@{JRIGHT} Section Head: @{"Tools" LINK "Tools"}@{line}
@{JCENTER}
@{B}IDLTm2@{UB}

_________________________________________________________________________

@{JLEFT}@{_LMARG_}

@{i}IDLTm2 @{ui} is a program to take the AOS4 library interface description XML file and produce a Modula-2 Definition module file that can (with some additional edits) be used to call the library directly from M2 programs and implementation modules. ie., something of a Modula-2 analog of the SDK program @{i}IDLTool @{ui}.@{line}

@{_Heading_ "PgmTemplate"}
-infil/A,-impl=implement/S,-version/S,-help/S@{_LRGDENT_}@{line}

-infil@{tab}The XML file describing the Amiga library interface(s).@{line}
-impl@{tab}Produce a skeleton Implementation module as well as the Definition module.@{_SMLDENT_}@{line}

The version with this release is v1.0 (16.12.2009).@{line}

The XML files for the standard Amiga Libraries are distributed with the SDK and named appropriately for their library, eg, for diskfont.library this is "diskfont.xml".@{line}
@{_LMARG_}

@{_Heading_ "Output"}
The output file will be will be a draft version of the DEFINITION MODULE for the interface(s), named by adding "Interfaces" to the library name, eg, "diskfontInterfaces.def", and, optionally, a draft version of the IMPLEMENTATION MODULE with autoopen code included.@{line}

These will require a little editing before use.@{line}

@{i}IDLTm2 @{ui} will automatically create the declarations for a constant containing the library name, and variables to hold the library base and the interface (pointer) itself. eg,@{_LRGDENT_}@{line} 

CONST diskfontLibName = "diskfont.library";@{line}
VAR   DiskfontBase :LibraryPtr;@{line}
TYPE DiskfontIFacePtr = POINTER TO DiskfontIFace;@{line}
VAR   IDiskfont   :DiskfontIFacePtr;@{_SMLDENT_}@{line}

And, of course, the RECORD containing the definitions of the interface's procedures. @{i}IDLTm2 @{ui} translates the parameters to each procedure and function into compatible, but often not ideal, M2 data types. A little knowledge of the SDK AutoDocs and the Aglet implementation will often allow you to edit the initially produced definition into something equivalent, but better suited to Modula-2. For example you can often avoid C's lack of arrays as parameters knowing that @{_AGM2_} passes all arrays (and records) by reference, whether VAR or non-VAR. Thus, the original output of @{i}IDLTm2 @{ui}:@{_LRGDENT_}@{line}

OpenOutlineFont :PROCEDURE(DiskfontIFacePtr, (*name*)ADDRESS, ListPtr,@{line}
                                      (*flags*)CARDINAL):OutlineFontPtr;@{_SMLDENT_}@{line}

can be manually edited to a better declaration:@{_LRGDENT_}@{line}

OpenOutlineFont :PROCEDURE(DiskfontIFacePtr, (*name*)ARRAY OF CHAR, ListPtr,@{line}
                                      (*flags*)BITSET32):OutlineFontPtr;@{_SMLDENT_}@{line}

@{i}IDLTm2 @{ui} knows about a few of these optimizations (eg, it will always translate "const struct TagItem *" as "ARRAY OF TagItem", but most you will need to do yourself (if you want the best DEFINITION file).@{_LMARG_}@{line}

See @{" Amiga Library Calls " LINK "ALIB"} for more information.@{line}

In most cases, for Amiga libraries, I have kept the constants, types, and variables used by the library in separate DEFINITION module(s) from the interface's one. For the Reaction classes, however, I have added the class-associated types, consts, and variables to the @{i}IDLTm2 @{ui} produced DEFINITION file.@{_LMARG_}@{line}
@endnode
@node "TGm2" "TGm2"
@{JRIGHT} Section Head: @{"Tools" LINK "Tools"}@{line}
@{JCENTER}
@{B}TGm2 Test Generator Program@{UB}

_________________________________________________________________________

@{JLEFT}@{_LMARG_}

@{i}tgM2 @{ui} is a program to aide in unit testing of Modula-2 software. It takes as input a user-prepared test script (*.ts file) which specifies one or more tests of a procedure or code block to be executed and reported upon. @{i}tgM2 @{ui} writes out a Modula-2 program for this test suite. The output program itself writes its results to standard output.@{line}

@{i}tgM2 @{ui} owes its existence and most of its architecture to the Ada 95 test driver generator program @{i}tg @{ui} for Ada written by Andre Spiegel, along with the version of @{i}tg @{ui} for Modula-2 (still an Ada 95 program) adapted to generate Modula-2 scripts done by Ralf Reissing.@{line}

(See more documentation at "http://www.modula2.org/projects/tgM2.php")@{line}

A simple program, @{i}TestManager @{ui}, has been written for automated testing that uses @{i}tgM2 @{ui} and its *.ts files to generate, run, and report the results on large batches of test cases.@{line} 

The beginnings of a compiler regression testing suite is located in the "Validate/" subdirectory of the @{_AGM2_} distribution.
@endnode
@node "Support" "Modules"
@{JRIGHT} Section Head: @{"Aglet Implementation" LINK "Aglet_Implementation"}@{line}
 Next subsection: @{"Amiga Specific" LINK "Amiga_Specific"}@{line}
@{JCENTER}
@{B}AgletM2 Support Modules@{UB}

_________________________________________________________________________

@{JLEFT}

@{B}General Notes@{UB}
@{LINDENT 3}


These @{" AutoOpen " LINK "LibAutoOpen"} any Amiga libraries they use (in the module initialization code).@{line}

Only a few have some "thread safety" build into them. e.g, the modules Storage and SystemStorage, do wrap their internal critical sections in semaphores.@{_SMLDENT_}@{line} 

