@node "SimpleGUI" "SimpleGUI"
@{settabs 35 65}
@{JRIGHT} Section Head: @{"Aglet Support Modules" LINK "Support"}@{line}
@{JCENTER}
@{B}SimpleGUI Module@{UB}

_________________________________________________________________________

@{JLEFT}@{_LMARG_}


SimpleGUI is a module that provides easy access to Amiga Reaction window and gadget facilities.


Its approach is essentially that of "simple things should be simple" and that "complex things should be possible" with development from a simple starting point.@{line}

@{_HEADING_ "Reaction Details 'Abstracted out'"}
Though its implementation is Reaction based, it does abstract out the presented GUI ideas to an extent. (It actually derives from an Amiga-inspired Windows M2 implementation of SimpleGUI that has not yet been fully re-implemented).@{_LMARG_}@{line}

@{_HEADING_ "Multi-Window Input Thread"}
Besides the procedures for creating, customizing, and positioning windows and gadgets, SimpleGUI handles all the details of starting a higher-priority thread to monitor and buffer the incoming messages from multiple windows/gadgets.
@{_LMARG_}@{line}

@{_HEADING_ "Types, Attributes, and Procedures"}
A set of available gadgets, not dissimilar to Reaction's, is presented for use:@{line}

@{_M2_ "TYPE"}  Gadgs =@{tab}@{_TABDENT_}(LabelSG, StringSG, EditSG, IntegerSG, RealSG, ButtonSG, CheckBoxSG, RadioButtonsSG, ScrollerSG, ChooseSG, MenuSG, ListSG, FuelGaugeSG, SpaceSG, BoxSG, ContainerSG);@{_SMLDENT_}@{line}

One or more attributes, or "modifiers", can be applied to customize the gadgets' features and behavior:@{line} 

Modifiers   =@{tab}@{_TABDENT_}(Boxed, Static, Transparent, Emphasized, Sorted, HighCapacity, ReadOnly, HelpG, Disabled, SizeToFit, SizeToFitH, SizeToFitV, EqualSize, UserData);@{_SMLDENT_}@{line}

A number of different events may be retrieved in a simple procedure call by your program from the SimpleGUI event queue. Each event comes with associated information attached, such as its originating gadget/window, the mouse position, the menu select id:@{line}

WndoEvnts =@{tab}@{_TABDENT_}(NullEv, CloseEv, SizeEv, PositionEv, FocusInEv, FocusOutEv, SelectEv, DblClickEv, MenuEv, KbdEv, HelpEv, LButtonDnEv, LButtonUpEv, RButtonDnEv, RButtonUpEv, MButtonDnEv, MButtonUpEv, MMoveEv, PacerEv);@{_SMLDENT_}@{line}  

Procedures are used for creating, customizing, positioning, altering, etc, the gadgets. Some of the procedures apply to any of the Gadgs types, and other procedures are specific for one or two types.
@{_LMARG_}@{line}

@{_HEADING_ "A Work-In-Progress"}
SimpleGUI is definitely a work-in-progress, though complete enough to produce non-trivial GUIs (see the M2IDE, and program GuideMaker). New modifiers, increased orthogonality, and new Gadg types will be added to better take advantage more of Reaction's capabilities and to make using SimpleGUI easier.@{line}

Please see the documentation residing in the comment section of SimpleGUI.def for details.@{line}
@endnode
@node "SimpleGraphics" "SimpleGraphics"
@{JRIGHT} Section Head: @{"Aglet Support Modules" LINK "Support"}@{line}
@{JCENTER}
@{B}SimpleGraphics Module@{UB}

_________________________________________________________________________

@{JLEFT}@{_LMARG_}

SimpleGraphics is an object-oriented 2D graphics package for AOS4.


It derives from an M2 Windows API implementation that has been (partially so far) transported as a layer above Intuition and Graphics library.


When fully implemented it will still be mostly a plotting package, but should be useful and extendable via inheritance.


Classes in the basic package are:


@{_HEADING_ "Screen"}
A drawing surface, currently implemented by an Amiga Window.
@{_LMARG_}@{line}

@{_HEADING_ "BufferedScreen"}
An extension of class Screen, useful for animation.
@{_LMARG_}@{line}

@{_HEADING_ "GraphRegion"}
A rectangular regions within a screen.
@{_LMARG_}@{line}

@{_HEADING_ "GraphText"}
An extension of class GraphRegion that encloses text.
@{_LMARG_}@{line}

@{_HEADING_ "GraphPlot"}
An extension of class GraphRegion that includes a scaling REAL number coordinate system and drawing operations.
@{_LMARG_}@{line}

@{_HEADING_ "GraphPlotWithAxes"}
An extension of class GraphPlot that supports placement of one or more horizontal or vertical axes onto the plot.
@{_LMARG_}@{line}

@{_HEADING_ "GraphPlotIterator"}
A virtual class that can be used to draw data sets onto a GraphPlot.
@{_LMARG_}@{line}
@endnode
@node "Module_Obj" "Module_Obj"
@next "ExperimentalMods"
@tab 50
@{JRIGHT} Section Head: @{"Aglet Support Modules" LINK "Support"}@{line}
@{JCENTER}
@{B}Module Obj@{UB}

_________________________________________________________________________

@{JLEFT}@{_LMARG_}@{code}
   This module can be used to implement a true Object Oriented package in base Modula-2,
   including inheritance, method replacement by the child, with static and dynamic class
   membership for an object.

   In the future, if the ISO Modula-2 "Object Oriented Extensions" are implemented in this compiler, it will
   take care of all the "manual" tasks required here to do true O-O, and replace
   the need for this module.

   Nevertheless, in case you want to experiment, here is some guide for using module Obj:

   (Also see module SimpleGraphics, currently the only module I've written using Obj.) 
_______________________________________________________________________________

Some guides for using this correctly.@{_SMLDENT_}

----------------------------------
To Use a Class in a client program:
----------------------------------

           1. Declare variables of the class object type.

                 eg, VAR MyRegion :GraphRegion;

           2. Instantiate the variable as an object of that class via the classes ...New() procedure.

                 eg,  MyRegion := GraphRegionNew(0,0,0,0, RegionAttributesSet{}, MyScreen);

           3. Call the method procedures by referencing the methods in the method table like this:

                 eg,  MyRegion^.vf^.SetBackColor(MyRegion, BLACKscr);

              The first parameter in the method is always the object itself.

           4. Delete the object when finished.

                 eg,  GraphRegionDelete(MyRegion);

           Note that objects are only used via reference.
           You can use the procedure
               Obj.ooAssignRef(fromObj:ADDRESS; toClass:Class):ADDRESS;  ( or its synonym Obj.oo() )
           To safely assign an object of a child class to a variable of its parent class type (or any
           ancestor class).
 
-----------------------------------------
To Declare your own Class in a DEF module:
-----------------------------------------

           1. Declare the class object type as a pointer to a descriptor record for the class.

              eg,  TYPE  GraphRegion = POINTER TO GraphRegionDesc;

           2. Declare the class methods (or virtual functions) table as a record of procedure types,
              with each field in the record having the method name.

              eg, TYPE  GraphRegionVFsRec
                        = RECORD
                            IsA@{tab}:PROCEDURE(ADDRESS(*GraphRegion*), VAR ARRAY OF CHAR);
                            Refresh@{tab}:PROCEDURE(ADDRESS(*GraphRegion*));
                            Clear@{tab}:PROCEDURE(ADDRESS);    (* does not do a refresh *)
                            Resize@{tab}:PROCEDURE(ADDRESS, INTEGER(*xmin*), INTEGER(*ymin*),
                                                            INTEGER(*xmax*), INTEGER(*ymax*));
                            Getsize@{tab}:PROCEDURE(ADDRESS, VAR INTEGER(*xmin*), VAR INTEGER(*ymin*),
                                                            VAR INTEGER(*xmax*), VAR INTEGER(*ymax*));
                            SetBackColor@{tab}:PROCEDURE(ADDRESS, ScreenColors);
                            GetBackColor@{tab}:PROCEDURE(ADDRESS, VAR ScreenColors);
                            <etc>...
                          END;

              The first parameter must always point to the object itself. Make it of type ADDRESS to facilitate
              use of inheritance.

           3. To facilitate method override and generic references to the method table, declare consts by which
              you can refer to the method table slots.

              eg, CONST IsAVF@{tab}= 0;
                        RefreshVF@{tab}= 1;
                        ClearVF@{tab}= 2;
                        ResizeVF@{tab}= 3;
                        GetsizeVF@{tab}= 4;
                        SetBackColorVF@{tab}= 5;
                        GetBackColorVF@{tab}= 6;
                        <etc>...

           4. Declare the class object type record like this:

                 GraphRegionDesc =
                      RECORD CASE :BOOLEAN OF
                        TRUE:
                          dyncl@{tab}:Class;
                          vf@{tab}:POINTER TO GraphRegionVFsRec;
                      | FALSE:
                          base@{tab}:RootObjDesc;
                          obj@{tab}:ObjectView;
                      END END;

               The TRUE tagged variant view has the effect of producing objects whose dynamic class and method table
               is always at a known offset, the first two fields.

               The first field in the FALSE tagged variant view is always the descriptor record of the parent
               class, so all ancestors are included.
               The second field holds the static class pointer for your class, and any private data an object
               of your class has.

           5. Declare four class-level (ie, not in the object) functions for creation and destruction of objects:

              eg,  PROCEDURE GraphRegionNew(xmin, ymin, xmax, ymax:INTEGER;
                                            Attributes:RegionAttributesSet(*? = Bit(CLIPPED)*);
                                            scr:Screen):GraphRegion;
                   PROCEDURE GraphRegionConstruct(VAR gd:GraphRegionDesc; xmin, ymin, xmax, ymax:INTEGER;
                                                  Attributes:RegionAttributesSet(*? = Bit(CLIPPED)*);
                                                  scr:Screen);
                   PROCEDURE GraphRegionDelete(VAR g:GraphRegion);
                   PROCEDURE GraphRegionDestruct(VAR gd:GraphRegionDesc);

              Normally just use the ...New() and the ...Delete() calls, since they call the ...Construct()
              and ...Destruct() procedures internally.

              Other class-level, non method procedures can also be declared to act on objects.

           6. Declare a variable to be the "Class", an opaque type that maintains the internal information needed
              to process classes by Module Obj.

                 eg,  VAR GraphRegionClass  :Class;

----------------------------------------
To Declare a child Class in a DEF module:
----------------------------------------

           Follow all steps as above with the following additions:

           For #2, you may extend the method table with new procedures. Your method table record
           must match exactly the parents, but you can add new entries at the end.

             eg, TYPE  GraphPlotVFsRec
                          = RECORD
                              IsA@{tab}:PROCEDURE(ADDRESS(*GraphRegion*), VAR ARRAY OF CHAR);
                              Refresh@{tab} :PROCEDURE(ADDRESS);
                              Clear@{tab}:PROCEDURE(ADDRESS);    (* does not do a refresh *)
                              Resize@{tab}:PROCEDURE(ADDRESS, INTEGER(*xmin*), INTEGER(*ymin*),
                                                         INTEGER(*xmax*), INTEGER(*ymax*));
                              Getsize@{tab}:PROCEDURE(ADDRESS, VAR INTEGER(*xmin*), VAR INTEGER(*ymin*),
                                                         VAR INTEGER(*xmax*), VAR INTEGER(*ymax*));
                              SetBackColor@{tab}:PROCEDURE(ADDRESS, ScreenColors);
                              GetBackColor@{tab}:PROCEDURE(ADDRESS, VAR ScreenColors);
                              <etc>...
                                   (*-----end GraphRegion-----*)
                              SetScale@{tab}:PROCEDURE(ADDRESS(*GraphPlot*), REAL(*Worldxmin*), REAL(*Worldymin*),
                                                          REAL(*Worldxmax*), REAL(*Worldymax*));
                              GetScale@{tab} :PROCEDURE(ADDRESS, VAR REAL(*Worldxmin*),
                                                          VAR REAL(*Worldymin*), VAR REAL(*Worldxmax*),
                                                          VAR REAL(*Worldymax*));
                              SetForeColor@{tab}:PROCEDURE(ADDRESS, ScreenColors);
                              GetForeColor@{tab}:PROCEDURE(ADDRESS, VAR ScreenColors);
                              <etc>...
                            END;

           For #3, you must continue numbering the method table slots where the parent left off:

              eg,  SetScaleVF@{tab}= LastGraphRegionVF + 1;
                   GetScaleVF@{tab}= LastGraphRegionVF + 2;
                   SetForeColorVF@{tab}= LastGraphRegionVF + 3;
                   GetForeColorVF@{tab}= LastGraphRegionVF + 4;
                   <etc>...

              It is a good idea to use a const definition for the last parent slot number so that less
              editing is needed if you decide to change the number of parent methods.

           For #4, the object record has its parent in the place where we had the root class object record
           above.
              eg,  GraphPlotDesc =
                       RECORD CASE :BOOLEAN OF
                         TRUE:
                           dyncl@{tab}:Class;
                           vf@{tab}:POINTER TO GraphPlotVFsRec;
                       | FALSE:
                           grd@{tab}:GraphRegionDesc;
                           obj@{tab}:ObjectView;
                         (*pub@{tab}:GraphPlotPublicRec;*)
                       END END;

               The commented out shows here object public data would go, if there were any.

--------------------------------------------
To Implement your own Class in a IMP module:
--------------------------------------------

          1. Give the class a name as a const string.
             eg.
                 CONST GraphRegionClassName       = "GraphRegion";

          2. Declare any private data an object of your class will need.
             eg,

                 GraphRegionPrivate = POINTER TO GraphRegionPrivateRec;
                 GraphRegionPrivateRec = RECORD
                                           scrGR@{tab}:Screen;
                                           Resized@{tab}:BOOLEAN;
                                           Extent@{tab}:ExtentType;
                                           BgColor@{tab}:ScreenColors;
                                           rpGR@{tab}:RastPortPtr;
                                           Attrs@{tab}:RegionAttributesSet;
                                           myRefresh@{tab}:CustomRefreshProc;
                                         END;



          3. Create and "Register" your class in the module init code by calling Obj.Register()
             for the class and Obj.RegisterVF() for each method.

             eg,  GraphRegionClass := Obj.Register(GraphRegionClassName, LastGraphRegionVF+1,
                                                   SIZE(GraphRegionDesc), SIZE(GraphRegionPrivateRec),
                                                   Obj.RootClass);
                  <*ISOMode(Loose)*>
                  Obj.RegisterVF(GraphRegionClass, CAST(PROC, ADR(GraphRegionIsA)), IsAVF);
                  Obj.RegisterVF(GraphRegionClass, CAST(PROC, ADR(GraphRegionRefresh)), RefreshVF);
                  Obj.RegisterVF(GraphRegionClass, CAST(PROC, ADR(GraphRegionClear)), ClearVF);
                  Obj.RegisterVF(GraphRegionClass, CAST(PROC, ADR(GraphRegionResize)), ResizeVF);
                  Obj.RegisterVF(GraphRegionClass, CAST(PROC, ADR(GraphRegionGetsize)), GetsizeVF);
                  Obj.RegisterVF(GraphRegionClass, CAST(PROC, ADR(GraphRegionSetBackColor)), SetBackColorVF);
                  Obj.RegisterVF(GraphRegionClass, CAST(PROC, ADR(GraphRegionGetBackColor)), GetBackColorVF);
                  Obj.RegisterVF(GraphRegionClass, CAST(PROC, ADR(GraphRegionAddAttributesSet)), AddAttributesSetVF);
                  <etc>...
                  <*ISOMode(Strict)*>

          4. Write the New... and Construct... procedures for objects of this class.

             The New... procedure will usually be very simple.
             eg,
                   PROCEDURE GraphRegionNew(xmin, ymin, xmax, ymax:INTEGER;
                          Attributes:RegionAttributesSet(*? = Bit(CLIPPED)*);
                          scr:Screen):GraphRegion;
                   VAR  ret :GraphRegion;
                   BEGIN
                   NEW(ret);
                   GraphRegionConstruct(ret^, xmin, ymin, xmax, ymax, Attributes, scr);
                   RETURN ret;
                   END GraphRegionNew;

             The Construct... procedure will always first call its parent's Construct... procedure (which
             will be Obj.RootConstruct() if there is no other parent).
             Next it will call Obj.Runtime() to set up the dynamic status of the object and allocate space
             for any private data.
             Finally, it will do whatever is needed to initialize an object of your class, and will fill the private data
             eg,
                PROCEDURE GraphRegionConstruct(VAR gd:GraphRegionDesc; ...)
                BEGIN WITH gd DO
                   Obj.RootConstruct(base);
                   this := ADR(gd);
                   private := Obj.Runtime(this, GraphRegionClass);
                   WITH private^ DO
                   <etc>...

          5. Write the Delete... and Destruct... procedures for objects of this class.

             This is similar to the above, but reversed. ie, the Destruct... procedure disposes its private
             data and then calls its parent Destruct... procedure.

             Note that there is no root object destructor, however.

          6. Write a procedure for each method as defined in your "VFs" record type.
             eg,
                  PROCEDURE GraphRegionGetsize(this:GraphRegion; VAR xmin, ymin, xmax, ymax:INTEGER);
                  VAR  private   :GraphRegionPrivate;
                  BEGIN
                    private := this^.obj.priv;
                    WITH private^ DO
                      xmin := Extent[X, lo];  xmax := Extent[X, hi];
                      ymin := Extent[Y, lo];  ymax := Extent[Y, hi];
                    END
                  END GraphRegionGetsize;

              Object private data for your class can be referenced as shown above or by using Obj.VFEntry().

--------------------------------------------
To Implement a child Class in a IMP module:
--------------------------------------------

           Follow the same steps as above, with the exception that

           for #3, you need call Obj.RegisterVF() only for methods that are new for your child class
           or for methods of the parent class that you want to override.

           Similarly, for #6, you need only write the new or overridden methods.
           If you have overridden a parent class method, but want to call it from yours, you can use
           Obj.GetClassVF().
           eg,
               PROCEDURE GraphPlotResize(this:GraphPlot; xmin, ymin, xmax, ymax:INTEGER);
               VAR  private  :GraphPlotPrivate;
               VAR  GRResize :RECORD CASE :BOOLEAN OF
                                TRUE:  p: PROCEDURE(ADDRESS, INTEGER, INTEGER, INTEGER, INTEGER);
                              | FALSE: P: PROC;
                              END END;
               BEGIN
               private := this^.obj.priv;
               WITH private^ DO
                  Obj.GetClassVF(GraphRegionClass, GRResize.P, ResizeVF);
                  GRResize.p(this, xmin, ymin, xmax, ymax);
                  this^.vf^.SetScale(this, wxmin, wymin, wxmax, wymax);
               END;
               END GraphPlotResize;

 
@endnode
@node "Amiga_Specific" "Amiga_Specific"
@tab 13
@{JRIGHT} Section Head: @{"Aglet Implementation" LINK "Aglet_Implementation"}@{line}
 Next subsection: @{"Tips" LINK "Tips"}@{line}
@{JCENTER}
@{B}Amiga Specific Info@{UB}

_________________________________________________________________________@{_LMARG_}
@{line}@{JLEFT}


@{_HEADING_ "Program Return Code"}

The shell return value, $RC, will be automatically set to 20 or above if the program terminates due to an EXCEPTION (including Assertions.Assert() failure).@{line}

Otherwise, you can explicitly write to the variable SystemRTS.CLIReturnCode to set this value.@{line}@{_LMARG_}

@{_HEADING_ "Program Arguments - Shell and Workbench"}

ISO module ProgramArgs now has code to process arguments passed from the Workbench startup message
as well as from the CLI. The code attempts to pretty much allow the ToolTypes in the WB icon to be
the same as the CLI switches. This means that the Aglet module ArgsSupport usually will work transparently
whether the program started via the CLI or the Workbench.@{line}

There are some rules for how you should set up your program argument templates
and ToolTypes for this to work well.@{line}

@{_ITM16_}> the "Project" file(s) on which a "Tool" (program) starts up on, if any, must be the beginning arguments and must not require the CLI arg key (ie, no "/K")@{_ITEMEND_}

@{_ITM16_}> ToolTypes are turned into following key or key keyvalue strings as if they
had come from the CLI that way. ToolType lines beginning with a "(" are ignored,
so that this (informal?) way of documenting what ToolTypes are available without issuing them will still work.@{_ITEMEND_}

@{_ITM16_}> Multiple ToolType values separated by "|" may work for /F or /M CLI templates, but only if things are kept simple.@{_ITEMEND_}

@{_ITM16_}> all the ToolTypes in the (first) Project icon will be applied, AND all the ToolTypes which are in the Tool (program)
file icon but not in the (first) Project icon are also applied.@{_ITEMEND_}
@{_LMARG_}

@{_HEADING_ "Hooks"}

Amiga "Hooks" are used in @{_AGM2_} essentially as described in the Autodocs
for C hooks. You should, however, always use the procedure specially provided
in the Utility module as the .hEntry field of the Hook RECORD order to ensure
that any M2 required extra prolog and postlog processing is done.@{line}

For example, if you have written a String Gadget hook procedure:@{_LRGDENT_}@{line}
PROCEDURE sgHookProcedure(VAR hook:Hook; VAR wb:SGWork; VAR cmd:CARDINAL):CARDINAL;@{_SMLDENT_}@{line}
and allocated a HookPtr "hk", you can set up the Hook as:@{line}       
@{_LRGDENT_}@{line}
<*ISOMode(Loose)*>@{_LRGDENT_}@{line}
@{b}WITH@{ub} hk^ @{b}DO@{ub}@{line}
   hEntry := @{b}ADR@{ub}(Utility.M2HookStub);@{line}
   hSubEntry := @{b}ADR@{ub}(sgHookProcedure);@{line}
   hData := <whatever ptr>;@{line}
@{b}END@{ub};@{line}
<*ISOMode(Strict)*>@{line}
@{_SMLDENT_}@{line}
Note that the compiler pragmas are required here since the ISO definition of ADR() does not allow it to be applied to
procedures.@{line}
@endnode
@node "Tips" "Tips"
@{JRIGHT} Section Head: @{"Aglet Implementation" LINK "Aglet_Implementation"}@{line}
 Next subsection: @{"Debugging" LINK "Debugging"}@{line}
@{JCENTER}
@{B}Language and Compiler Tips@{UB}

_________________________________________________________________________@{_LMARG_}
@{line}@{JLEFT}


@{_HEADING_ "Report Problems"}
Tom Breeden@{line}
Aglet Software@{line}
tmb@virginia.edu
@{_LMARG_}@{line}

@{_HEADING_ "Use M2IDE"}
If at all possible, for non-trivial projects use the @{i}M2IDE @{ui} since it will track module import dependencies and compile your modules in the correct order (use "Update" on the program module after a "Refresh" if necessary).
@{line}

@{i}GoldEd @{ui} is a very nice commercial editor configurable for syntax coloring for Modula-2. It is still available for sale at Dietmar Eilert's pages on the web.@{line}

@{i}Turbotext @{ui} was a commercial editor that has now been made freely available. Turbotext V2 runs well on the latest release of AOS4. For download, see the URL http://www.monkeyhouse.eclipse.co.uk/amiga/turbotext/.@{line}

An editor interface is also provided for @{i}CygnusEd @{ui} and for the nice freeware editor, @{i}Annotate@{ui}, available on OS4Depot.@{_LMARG_}@{line}

@{_HEADING_ "Use the ISO Standard Library"}
There are a number of ISO compatible or ISO-like M2 compilers for other platforms, eg. GNU Modula-2.
@{_LMARG_}@{line}

@{_HEADING_ "Starting your program via a WB Icon"}
Programs can be started from a shell with Amiga style arguments, or from the WB with equivalent Tooltypes. You will usually want to set the icon's startup type to Shell.@{_LMARG_}@{line}

@{_HEADING_ "M2IDE: Placement of program source"}
Currently upon new project creation @{i}M2IDE @{ui} expects that the program source file will be in the current directory. You can get around this by adding your desired directory to the Source Files name list immediately after starting up @{i}M2IDE @{ui}, saving the project, and then restarting @{i}M2IDE @{ui} on the project, upon which the existing program (or program skeleton) file will be found. This will be stored in the .PRJ file so needs be done only at the start of a new project.
@{_LMARG_}@{line}

@{_HEADING_ "M2IDE: Watch out for source file errors in the IMPORT section"}
@{i}M2IDE @{ui} parses the import section on all files it can find, and uses that information to generate the dependency tree. If it does not seem to have identified all the necessary modules, or does not seem to be able to open a dependent module even though that module's path is in the Sources NameList,
check for syntax errors in the IMPORT section.
@{_LMARG_}@{line}

@{_HEADING_ "Asm Files"}
The compiler writes out the temporary #?.asm files (as well as #?.err files) to "T:". It does not delete these files, assuming that T: is assigned to RAM: or RAD:. If that is not the case on your system, you may want to clear out T: from time to time.@{line}

Object files (#?.o files) for implementation modules and Symbol files (#?.sbm) for definition modules are written to the
output directory (current directory) and should be kept around to avoid the necessity of re-compiling support modules.@{line}

@{_LMARG_}@{line}
@endnode
@node "Debugging" "Debugging"
@tab 65
@{JRIGHT} Section Head: @{"Aglet Implementation" LINK "Aglet_Implementation"}@{line}
@{JCENTER}
@{B}Debugging Tips@{UB}@{line}
_________________________________________________________________________@{line}@{JLEFT}@{_LMARG_}

Currently there is no source level debugger for @{_AGM2_}, but there are a number of ways to get debugging information (in addition to the tried and true one of inserting write statements in the code using the standard modules STextIO and SWholeIO).@{line}

Also, note that the compiler will identify and generate no code for source statements that are clearly unreachable. To be able to eliminate easily almost all of the run-time overhead of a debugging statement, declare a constant at the top of your module such as@{_LRGDENT_}@{line}

@{_M2_ "CONST"} DEBUG = TRUE;@{_LMARG_}@{line}

and surround your debugging statements with @{_M2_ "IF DEBUG THEN ... END"}. Simply changing the constant to FALSE and re-compiling will remove the debugging code from the output object file.@{par}

Other debugging possibilities include:@{_SMLDENT_}@{line}

Module SymbolsRTS@{tab}@{" > " LINK "SymbolsRTSDebug"}

Modules Debugging and Assertions@{tab}@{" > " LINK "ModDebug"}

Module DebugIO@{tab}@{" > " LINK "ModDebugIO"}

Verbose Compile and Link@{tab}@{" > " LINK "VerboseCompile"}

Code Listing Compile@{tab}@{" > " LINK "CodeListing"}

Grim Reaper Info@{tab}@{" > " LINK "GrimReaper"}

GDB@{tab}@{" > " LINK "GDB"}@{line}
@endnode
@node "SymbolsRTSDebug" "SymbolsRTSDebug"
@{JRIGHT} Section Head: @{"Debugging" LINK "Debugging"}@{line}
 Next subsection: @{"MODULE Debugging" LINK "ModDebug"}@{line}
@{JCENTER}
@{B}SymbolsRTS@{UB}

_________________________________________________________________________@{_LMARG_}@{line}
@{JLEFT}

If you put an "IMPORT SymbolsRTS;" into your Program module, this enables the default
error-trapping routines to report the error location in terms of the module and procedure name
from the source code.@{line}

ie, you will get a message on exception like this:@{_LRGDENT_}@{line}
,-------------------------------------@{line}
| @{b}M2EXCEPTION@{ub}                @{line}
|-------------------------------------@{line}
|      wholeDivException              @{line}
|     ThisModule.ThisProc             @{line}
'-------------------------------------@{line}@{_LMARG_}

rather than this:@{_LRGDENT_}@{line}
,-------------------------------------@{line}
| @{b}M2EXCEPTION@{ub}                @{line}
|-------------------------------------@{line}
|      wholeDivException              @{line}
|         0x7fc0df7c                  @{line}
'-------------------------------------@{line}@{_LMARG_}

To get the best results, you should also use the "-incldbg" ("-g") switch with Mod2Lnk,
which includes non-exported procedure names into the executable.@{line}

In addition, your own exception handlers may be able to make use of the procedure
SymbolsRTS.FindSourcePos() to report in the same way on any address within the code.
(The LineNum return value is not yet implemented). 
@endnode
@node "ModDebug" "ModDebug"
@{JRIGHT} Section Head: @{"Debugging" LINK "Debugging"}@{line}
 Next subsection: @{"MODULE DebugIO" LINK "ModDebugIO"}@{line}
@{JCENTER}
@{B}DEFINITION MODULE Debugging;@{UB}

_________________________________________________________________________@{_LRGDENT_}@{line}
@{JLEFT}

This debugging module can pause and show some information or write it into a debugging window.@{lindent 0}@{line}
@{JCENTER}
_________________________________________________________________________
@{_LMARG_}@{line}@{JLEFT}

@{_M2_ "PROCEDURE"} Debug(msg:@{_M2_ "ARRAY OF CHAR"}; i:@{_M2_ "INTEGER"});@{line}
@{_M2_ "PROCEDURE"} DebugPause(msg:@{_M2_ "ARRAY OF CHAR"}; i:@{_M2_ "INTEGER"});@{line}

@{_M2_ "PROCEDURE"} DebugOn(DebugLine:@{_M2_ "CARDINAL"});

@{_M2_ "PROCEDURE"} DebugOff;@{line}
@{_M2_ "PROCEDURE"} DebugQuery(msg:@{_M2_ "ARRAY OF CHAR"});@{line}

@{_M2_ "PROCEDURE"} IsDebugOn():@{_M2_ "BOOLEAN"};@{line}

@{_M2_ "PROCEDURE"} DebugMemory();@{line}
@{_M2_ "PROCEDURE"} DebugStack();@{line}

______________________________________________________________________________________________@{line}

 
@{JCENTER}
@{B}DEFINITION MODULE Assertions;@{UB}

_________________________________________________________________________@{line}
@{JLEFT}


 @{_M2_ "PROCEDURE"} Assert(b:@{_M2_ "BOOLEAN"}; msg:@{_M2_ "ARRAY OF CHAR"});@{line}
    (* EXCEPTION if b is not true *)@{line}
@{line}
 @{_M2_ "PROCEDURE"} AssertWarn(b:@{_M2_ "BOOLEAN"}; msg:@{_M2_ "ARRAY OF CHAR"});@{line}
    (* Warns if b is not true, then continues *)@{line}
@{line}
 @{_M2_ "PROCEDURE"} IsAssertException():@{_M2_ "BOOLEAN"};@{line}
@endnode
@node "ModDebugIO" "ModDebugIO"
@{JRIGHT} Section Head: @{"Debugging" LINK "Debugging"}@{line}
 Next subsection: @{"Verbose Compile" LINK "VerboseCompile"}@{line}
@{JCENTER}
@{B}DEFINITION MODULE DebugIO;@{UB}

_________________________________________________________________________@{_LRGDENT_}@{line}
@{JLEFT}

Use this debugging module when you want to minimize the dependency on other working M2 code. It is simply a call to the AOS4 library procedure TimedDosRequester() with a 60 second timeout.@{lindent 0}@{line}
@{JCENTER}
_________________________________________________________________________
@{_LMARG_}@{line}@{JLEFT}

@{_M2_ "PROCEDURE"} DebugIOMsg(Title, Text:@{_M2_ "ARRAY OF CHAR"}; Buttons:@{_M2_ "ARRAY OF CHAR"}):@{_M2_ "INTEGER"};@{line}

      (* Use "|" to separate multiple buttons *)@{line}
      (* returns      1, 2, 3, ..., N, 0 indicate which choice, left to right, was taken *)@{line}
      (*     NOTE:   > Leftmost choice always 1, rightmost always 0.                     *)@{line}
@endnode
@node "VerboseCompile" "VerboseCompile"
@{JRIGHT} Section Head: @{"Debugging" LINK "Debugging"}@{line}
 Next subsection: @{"Code Listing" LINK "CodeListing"}@{line}
@{JCENTER}
@{B}Verbose Compile Listing@{UB}

_________________________________________________________________________

@{JLEFT}@{_LMARG_}

Using the "-verbose" compiler switch will display the name of each imported symbol file as it is read, and, more importantly, will display each procedure name being processed as well as the phase of processing it is in.@{line}

If, in the unfortunate (and hopefully, increasingly unlikely) case that the compiler runs into an error from which it cannot recover, you can still discover in which procedure the problem occurred, as well as the compiler operation (parsing, optimizing, code generation, or file output).@{line}

Here is an example of the output for a verbose compile:@{line}
_________________________________________________________________________
@{b}

Mod2 v3.0 Compiler Alpha0 (3.4.2008)@{line}
Copyright (c) 2004 by Thomas Breeden@{line}
GuideMaker.mod@{line}@{ub}

 <- M2Lv3:SystemRTS.SBM@{line}
 <- M2Lv3:Assertions.SBM@{line}
     ... <etc>@{line}
 <- AmigaGuideCmdStructs.SBM@{line}
 <- AmigaGuideFormat.SBM@{line}
 <- AmigaGuideParser.SBM@{line}
 <- AmigaGuideSyntax.SBM@{line}
 <- AmigaGuideSyntax.SBM@{line}
 <- GuideMakerDefs.SBM@{line}
 <- GuideMakerGUI.SBM@{line}
 <- GuideMakerInput.SBM@{line}
 <- GuideMakerNodeProcess.SBM@{line}
 <- GuideMakerShow.SBM@{line}
     ... <etc>@{line}
 <- M2Lv3:Str1.SBM@{line}@{b}

Delay   Parse-Optim-Gen-Out@{line}
InitPgm   Parse-Optim-Gen-Out@{line}
GetArgs   Parse-Optim-Gen-Out@{line}
GetFile   Parse-Optim-Gen-Out@{line}
NodeIndexArg   Parse-Optim-Gen-Out@{line}
CmdIndexArg   Parse-Optim-Gen-Out@{line}
NewNodeArgs   Parse-Optim-Gen-Out@{line}
ShowNodeArgs   Parse-Optim-Gen-Out@{line}
EditNodeArgs   Parse-Optim-Gen-Out@{line}
NewLinkArgs   Parse-Optim-Gen-Out@{line}
NewAttrArgs   Parse-Optim-Gen-Out@{line}
UpdCmdArgs   Parse-Optim-Gen-Out@{line}
NewCmdArgs   Parse-Optim-Gen-Out@{line}
FileNameArgs   Parse-Optim-Gen-Out@{line}
WriteItOut   Parse-Optim-Gen-Out@{line}
ProcessLoop   Parse-Optim-Gen-Out@{line}
GuideMaker   Parse-Optim-Gen-Out@{line}
 -> GuideMaker.asm@{line}@{ub}

Optimize Setting: DeadCode@{line}
SDK:gcc/bin/as -o GuideMaker.o GuideMaker.asm 0@{line}

.
@endnode
@node "CodeListing" "CodeListing"
@font "Bitstream Vera Sans Mono.font" 12
@{JRIGHT} Section Head: @{"Debugging" LINK "Debugging"}@{line}
 Next subsection: @{"Grim Reaper" LINK "GrimReaper"}@{line}
@{JCENTER}
@{B}Compiler Code Listing@{UB}

_________________________________________________________________________

@{JLEFT}@{_LMARG_}

Using the "-list" compiler switch will produce a detailed listing including the source lines, the intermediate code, and the PPC Native code.@{line}

For example:@{line}
_________________________________________________________________________

@{code}
 128 
 129 (*--------------------------------------*)
 130  PROCEDURE Delay(secs, millis:CARDINAL);
 131 (*--------------------------------------*)
 132 
                         |-------------Delay Entry-------------
                         procentry Delay
                         ;DetermineFrameSize
                         ;save LR in caller's frame
                            mfspr %r0,8
                            stw %r0,4(%r1)
                         ;alloc stack frame and save regs (STATIC)
                            or %r11,%r1,%r1
                            stwu %r1,-64(%r1)
                            stw %r29,-12(%r11)
                            stw %r30,-8(%r11)
                            stw %r31,-4(%r11)
                         ;establish the mp linkage
                            stw %r14,12(%r1)
                            addi %r14,%r1,12
                         ;Move the overflow params
                         ;Move the HIGH values
                         ;DoStructureParmCopies
                         ;Copy the static refcpyparams
                         ;Copy the dynamic params
                         ;ExitBasicBlockPre
                            stw %r3,8(%r14)
                            stw %r4,12(%r14)
                         ;ExitBasicBlockPost
                         |-------------Delay BlockCode-------------
 133 VAR  t    :AmigaTimer.TimerHandle;
 134      bRes :BOOLEAN;
 135 
 136 BEGIN
 137 
 138 bRes := AmigaTimer.OpenATimer(t, 1);
                         prepcall OpenATimer
                         paramref t OpenATimer $c0(0H)
                            addi %r3,%r14,16
                         paramcpy $c1(1H) OpenATimer $c1(1H)
                            addi %r4,0,1
                         ;ExitBasicBlockPre
                         callext OpenATimer -> $t1
                            bl 0
                            or %r31,%r3,%r3
                         ;ExitBasicBlockPost
                         copy $t1 -> bRes
                            or %r30,%r31,%r31
 139 bRes := AmigaTimer.SleepATimer(t, secs, 1000*millis);
                         prepcall SleepATimer
                         mul $c1000(3E8H) millis -> $t2
                            lwz %r29,12(%r14)
                            mulli %r31,%r29,1000
                         paramcpy t SleepATimer $c0(0H)
                            lwz %r3,16(%r14)
                         paramcpy secs SleepATimer $c1(1H)
                            lwz %r4,8(%r14)
                         paramcpy $t2 SleepATimer $c2(2H)
                            or %r5,%r31,%r31
                         ;ExitBasicBlockPre
                            stb %r30,20(%r14)
                         callext SleepATimer -> $t3
                            bl 0
                            or %r31,%r3,%r3
                         ;ExitBasicBlockPost
                         copy $t3 -> bRes
                            or %r30,%r31,%r31
 140 bRes := AmigaTimer.CloseATimer(t);
                         prepcall CloseATimer
                         paramref t CloseATimer $c0(0H)
                            addi %r3,%r14,16
                         ;ExitBasicBlockPre
                            stb %r30,20(%r14)
                         callext CloseATimer -> $t4
                            bl 0
                            or %r31,%r3,%r3
                         ;ExitBasicBlockPost
                         copy $t4 -> bRes
                            or %r30,%r31,%r31
 141 
 142 END Delay;
                         ;ExitBasicBlockPre
                            stb %r30,20(%r14)
                         ;ExitBasicBlockPost
                         |-------------Delay Exit-------------
                         procexit Delay
                            lwz %r14,0(%r14)
                            addi %r11,%r1,64
                            lwz %r29,-12(%r11)
                            lwz %r30,-8(%r11)
                            lwz %r31,-4(%r11)
                            lwz %r1,0(%r1)
                            lwz %r0,4(%r1)
                            mtspr 8,%r0
                            bclr 20,0
                         ;ExitBasicBlockPre
                         ;ExitBasicBlockPost@{line}

.
@endnode
@node "GrimReaper" "GrimReaper"
@{JRIGHT} Section Head: @{"Debugging" LINK "Debugging"}@{line}
 Next subsection: @{"GDB" LINK "GDB"}@{line}
@{JCENTER}
@{B}Grim Reaper@{UB}

_________________________________________________________________________

@{JLEFT}@{_LMARG_}

In some (desperate) situations inserting a "breakpoint" into the source code, along with knowledge of @{" Low Level " LINK "LowLevel"} compiler information and a bit of PPC Assembly language, can throw light on an obscure malfunction.@{line}

The inline assembly language feature of @{_AGM2_} responds to the (non-standard) PPC instruction, "illegal", by breaking into the Grim Reaper at exactly that point in the code sequence.@{line}

for example the program:@{_SMLDENT_}@{line}

(*###################*)@{line}
 MODULE TstGrimReaper;@{line}
(*###################*)@{line}
VAR  i, j:INTEGER;@{line}
      (*-------------------------------------*)@{line}
       PROCEDURE P(j:INTEGER; VAR i:INTEGER);@{line}
      (*-------------------------------------*)@{line}
      BEGIN@{line}
      <*Asm(ON)*>@{line}
      illegal@{line}
      <*Asm(OFF)*>@{line}
      i := j+17;@{line}
      END P;@{line}
BEGIN@{line}
i := 11;@{line}
j := 13;@{line}
P(j, i);@{line}
END TstGrimReaper.@{_LMARG_}@{line}

Will produce this @{" GR " LINK "Gr3.jpg/MAIN"} upon reaching the "illegal".@{line}

If @{" r3 " LINK "Gr4.jpg/MAIN"} does not contain 13, or the mem location pointed to by @{" r4 " LINK "Gr5.jpg/MAIN"} does not contain 11 at that point, you know that something has gone seriously wrong before then.@{line}

You can "@{u}C@{uu}ontinue Program" after this "breakpoint" with no ill-effects.@{line}
@endnode
@node "GDB" "GDB"
@{JRIGHT} Section Head: @{"Debugging" LINK "Debugging"}@{line}
@{JCENTER}
@{B}GDB@{UB}@{line}
_________________________________________________________________________@{line}@{JLEFT}@{_LMARG_}

A determined and patient programmer with a good knowledge of assembly code may be able to make some use of GDB.@{par}

Even without debugging symbols, the Elf executable will have a symbol table that includes the addresses of the entry points of all modules and procedures. You can use the GDB command "info functions" to see these addresses, and then insert breakpoints as desired.@{par}

Nevertheless, I find GDB extremely difficult to use, but have been able to use it to tease out information I needed about what was happening at program startup, before the modules DebugIO or Debugging are usable.@{par}

.
@endnode
@node "M2_Examples" "M2_Examples"
@tab 42
@{JRIGHT} Prev section: @{"Aglet Implementation" LINK "Aglet_Implementation"}@{line}
 Next section: @{"IDE Tutorial" LINK "IDE_Tutorial"}@{line}
@{JCENTER}
@{B}Some Example and Test Programs@{UB}

_________________________________________________________________________

@{JLEFT}@{_LMARG_}


@{_HEADING_ "Classic"}
HelloWorld@{line}
@{_LMARG_}

@{_HEADING_ "Intuition etc."}
ReadFontPrefs@{tab}@{lindent 43}-Lists the five user-settable Prefs fonts (WB Icon, Drawer Icon, Drawer Text, System Default, and Screen Font)@{_SMLDENT_}@{line}
ReadPubScreens@{tab}@{lindent 43}-Lists the names of all the Public Screens the user has set up with Prefs.@{_SMLDENT_}@{line}
